Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: FDA ORA Regulatory Business Information Services
Project Name: FDA ORA RBIS Data Warehouse, Data Marts, and Universes
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Online Reporting Analysis and Decision Support System (ORADSS) within RBIS contains a Data Warehouse (DW) at its core.  This provides access to historical data from a number of systems, such as MARCS. The DW further contains a reporting database that retains the schema from the Online Transaction Processing (OLTP) database from which information was originated. The DW has information in it that has been transformed into a star schema so that it is a Decision Support System (DSS). In addition, for some user communities, it is much more effective for them to only have to deal with a subset of all of the data in the DW. For such user communities, ORADSS has a number of Data Marts (DM) that certain designated users can use for querying. These are also used to support universes for reporting. ORADSS uses a COTS, Business Objects (BO), as a reporting tool. BO utilizes universes as a meta-data layer that allows for an abstraction of the underlying schema, table names, row names, and data types so that non technical users can access this data more easily. The universe structures may then be used to build reports. End users typically interact with the reports, but there are a number of end users who need to delve more deeply into the data than is allowed by a report. These users may access the DW, DMs, or universes directly depending on their particular needs. This project specifically focuses on providing better data availability for compliance users, MARCS Predictive Risk-based Evaluation and Dynamic Import Compliance Targeting (PREDICT), and an organizational group in ORA that tracks resources and conducts work force planning.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: FDA ORA Regulatory Business Information Services
Project Name: FDA ORA RBIS Firm Master List Services (FMLS) Enhancements
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: FMLS in RBIS is closely aligned with Firm Management Services (FMS) in MARCS. FMLS does the back end heavy lifting work for managing firm information. This includes receiving firm information from registration and listing from the FDA Unified Registration and Listing System (FURLS). FURLS is being partially replaced by eLIST. FMLS will integrate with eLIST (no acronym). The firm data is built around Firm Establishment Identifiers (FEIs). These define a location and a product or a set of products. A large company may have multiple FEIs if it has multiple physical locations and/or produces different products that are regulated by FDA. This information is always changing as firms and market conditions change.  In addition, foreign firms that do not use a Latin alphabet present a particular problem as words can be transliterated into English in different ways. If this is left unchecked, it causes a proliferation of FEIs that are not all that useful in identifying what firm is what. To address this, FMLS employs Dataflux, a COTS, in implementing survivorship rules that are used to clean up this firm data and consolidate and remove FEIs. FMLS is also being integrated with Dunn and Bradstreet (DnB). DnB has one of the largest and most reliable databases on businesses in the world. This is being leveraged to improve the quality of firm information, especially that related to foreign firms. This project focuses primarily on integrating with eLIST, improving survivorship rules and their application, and integrating with DnB. This provides MARCS FMS with access to higher quality data in regards to firms, which is used throughout the ORA regulatory work flows.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: FDA ORA Regulatory Business Information Services
Project Name: FDA ORA RBIS Report Development Support
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Online Reporting Analysis and Decision Support System (ORADSS) contains well over a thousand reports. This project will undertake a review of these reports to see what can be consolidated. In addition, it will provide a number of new reports to users. The types and number of reports is continually changing as the needs of users changes. ORADSS provides historical information and reporting capabilities to Mission Accomplishments and Regulatory Compliance Services (MARCS).  Essentially, this makes every user of MARCS a user of ORADSS. As MARCS continues to build towards a unified data structure, this will require changes in ORADSS in order to provide historical information and reporting capabilities. These changes in MARCS will result in a number of changes to reports on the ORADSS side. In addition, ORADSS will also provide historical information and reporting capabilities for the Automated Laboratory Management (ALM) Laboratory Management Information System (LIMS). LIMS is planning to produce pilots in FY12. This project will also lay the groundwork for providing reports for LIMS users.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: FDA ORA Regulatory Business Information Services
Project Name: FDA ORA RBIS Data Evaluation and Recommendations
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: RBIS has grown organically over time. With the recently awarded contract that places RBIS under one contractor, the changes in Mission Accomplishments and Regulatory Compliance Services (MARCS), and the expected addition of Automated Laboratory Management (ALM) Laboratory Information Management System (LIMS), it is time to review the design of RBIS. This project will conduct a full review of the technical structure and implementation of the Online Reporting Analysis and Decision Support System (ORADSS) and Firm Master List Services (FMLS). RBIS provides the historical information, reporting capabilities, and firm information that are needed by MARCS and ALM. Changes in MARCS and ALM need to be accommodated in RBIS in order to provide end user functionality. This project will provide recommendations to the Government as to how to best restructure RBIS to handle expected future growth. This will also result in a road map to align RBIS future development with MARCS and ALM.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: FDA ORA Regulatory Business Information Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: This project focuses primarily on the RBIS Online Reporting Analysis and Decision Support System (ORADSS) and provides for changes to support Mission Accomplishments and Regulatory Compliance Services (MARCS) and Automated Laboratory Management (ALM). ORADSS provides historical information and reporting capabilities to MARCS and ALM. As MARCS continues to build towards a unified data structure, this will require changes in ORADSS in order to provide historical information and reporting capabilities. These changes in MARCS will result in a number of changes to reports on the ORADSS side. In addition, ORADSS will also provide historical information and reporting capabilities for the ALM Laboratory Management Information System (LIMS) and the ALM Quality Management Information System (QMiS). This will also provide for improvements in mapping capabilities regarding firm information. This will result in changes within ORADSS to the Data Warehouse (DW), many of the Data Marts (DMS), universes, and reports. ORADSS uses the COTS Business Objects as the basis for universe and reporting functionality.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: FDA ORA Regulatory Business Information Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: This project focuses primarily on Firm Master List Services (FMLS). This includes additional Center integration, gray area resolution, additional support for Dunn and Bradstreet (DnB) integration, and improved integration with  Mission Accomplishments and Regulatory Compliance Services (MARCS) Predictive Risk-based Evaluation and Dynamic Import Compliance Targeting (PREDICT) for validating firm information. FDA receives much firm information via Center systems, including FDA Unified Registration and Listing System (FURLS) and eLIST (no acronym). This will focusing on improving and automating more of this information transfer. Gray area resolution is used to resolve uncertainties regarding firm information when the survivorship rules used in FMLS do not produce a clear resolution. Survivorship rules are implemented via the COTS Dataflux and are an automated way to correct firm data, merge, unmerge, and delete Firm Establishment Identifiers (FEI). Manual gray area resolution is performed to tweak survivorship rules and manually resolve information discrepancies. DnB integration will be expanded, including a review of the current firm inventory in ORA and matching these against DnB information to produce a confidence level from 1 to 10 (10 is highest confidence) to support estimating the risk associated with a firm based on the quality of firm information. This will be used to support risk based decisions such as used for import screening. The method used to validate firm information from Customs and Border Protection (CBP) that is then used by PREDICT in import screening will be modified to improve this, reduce latency, reduce uncertainty, and reduce reprocessing. FMLS in RBIS is closely aligned with Firm Management Services (FMS) in MARCS. FMLS does the back end heavy lifting work for managing firm information. As FMS is modified, FMLS will also be modified to support expanded functionality for MARCS users.

This project focuses primarily on the RBIS Online Reporting Analysis and Decision Support
System (ORADSS) and provides for changes to support Mission Accomplishments and
Regulatory Compliance Services (MARCS) and Automated Laboratory Management (ALM).

also provide historical information and reporting capabilities for the ALM Laboratory
Management Information System (LIMS) and the ALM Quality Management Information
System (QMiS). This will also provide for improvements in mapping capabilities regarding firm
information. This will result in changes within ORADSS to the Data Warehouse (DW), many of
the Data Marts (DMS), universes, and reports. ORADSS uses the COTS Business Objects as the
basis for universe and reporting functionality.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: FDA ORA Regulatory Business Information Services
Project Name: FDA ORA RBIS Regulatory Data Management and Analytics
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
Regulatory Business Information Services’ (RBIS) project objectives are to provide data management services, data warehousing and analytics capabilities. RBIS will integrate data from other FRDA Business Centers and ORA repositories, to present a single view of data across FDA. RBIS will provide a single source of data for ORA’s inspection locations (establishments) and provide services associated with these inspection locations. 

RBIS will enable centers to obtain establishment and ORA field operations data in order to implement workforce planning, establish food safety policies, and enforce compliance programs on regulated products. RBIS identifies and removes duplicate firms from ORA's inspection location inventory. RBIS provides web services to validate addresses and match firms within the establishment inventory.

RBIS will provide a search capability to view structured and unstructured data including: Field Accomplishment Computerized Tracking System (FACTS) inspection data, establishment inspection Reports, FDA 483 Observations report, firm details and history data, and recall information. RBIS includes a critical 24/7 application supporting field entry reviewers in the admissibility decisions of import operations. RBIS will provide over 25 Business Intelligence Universes for ad-hoc reporting, over 1,000 pre-defined reports and over 70,000 user-defined reports supporting a wide variety of functions across FDA.

RBIS will be used by ORA Investigators, Inspectors, Import Screeners, Supervisors, Branch Directors, District Directors, Technicians, Coordinators, State Contract Monitors, Compliance Officers, and Planners, Program Managers, Firm Data Stewards, and Risk-based Input users. Also, personnel supporting the CFSAN, CDER, CTP and CDRH centers are customers that will consume RBIS services.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: FDA OC Financial Management Information Systems
Project Name: FDA OC User Fee System Enhancements
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: All major functions of UFFRS are available to users through its three production systems.  However, changes to respond to Legislative actions and/or regulations that require corresponding IT adjustments, technical upgrades, or internal business or administrative requirements from the FDA user community are frequent, and usually cannot be anticipated in advance.  The User Fee System contract for O&M supports such changes under individual IDEA Task Orders.  Most are Fixed Price and range from $.050M to $.500M.  Estimated funding for  Task Orders was identified as "activities" in the FY14 submission.  However, because of their type and limited size, and the inability to accurately project Task Order start dates, durations, or actual costs until awarded, HHS has recommended the User Fee system be managed as an O&M investment.  As a result of that change, only enhancements that require significant additional resources or pose major risks will be identified as projects.  No enhancements that meet those criteria are anticipated FY13 for FY14. All activities initiated with FY13 or FY14 funding will be reported until completion.

Specifically, to remediate the following internal control deficiencies identified as part of the OMB A-123 Appendices A and C, related to invoices on type Y contracts, i.e. contracts awarded by OAGS.   ·           Automate the CO Holds, COR Holds and Amount Billed Exceeds Amount Received processes in support of identifying and removing invoice holds on vendor invoices ·        Automate invoice review for FAR and Prompt Payment Act compliance as well as ensuring the arithmetic is correct in the invoices for quantity and dollar value compared to total billed amount within the invoice (for Illumina, DRT, I3, and Remy).   Remediating these internal control deficiencies, proactively mitigating inherent risks and automating processes susceptible to human error will reduce improper and inaccurate payments, reduce expenses, increase savings, and reduce risks of interruption in services from vendors because of delays in payments.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: FDA OC Financial Management Information Systems
Project Name: FDA OC FMIS Integrated Budget and Acquisition Planning Systems Call#11
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: "The objective is to implement  Working Capital Fund (WCF) Enhancements Implementation Support  - To be completed as part of IBAPS Release 17. The Office of Finance Budget and Acquisition (OFBA) is seeking Contractor support for implementation of changes in the IBAPS solution to support the FDA’s Working Capital Fund (WCF) initiative. The focus of this call order will be to implement new features and/or enhancements required in the current IBAPS Solution to support the working capital fund (WCF) implementation at FDA. A Working Capital Fund (WCF) is a revolving fund authorized by law to finance a cycle of operation. It is a method of financing certain administrative services in a manner different than funding them through annual appropriations. A WCF, therefore, is not an appropriation. Instead it’s a financing mechanism which: • Generates revenue from the sale of goods and services • Recoups the cost of doing business through customer payments • Emphasizes commercial business practices as its method of operation FDA is implementing the WCF in FY19 and the WCF will be operational in FY19 with the WCF Service Providers billing the FDA Centers and offices for the services provided. As part of this call order, FDA is seeking contractor support to develop enhancements to support WCF requirements. Major Enhancement 1: Additional ability to automate Miscellaneous data entry for Center split funded bill (June Release) Major Enhancement 2: Ability to generate a data file at a CAN level to help automate creation of the Center’s POs (September Release)".

The Food Safety Modernization Act (FSMA) requires the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) to establish a voluntary, fee-based program for the expedited review and importation of foods from importers who achieve and maintain a high level of control over the safety and security of their supply chains. Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: HHS Unified Financial Management System (UFMS) Investment
Project Name: UFMS Release 12 (R12) Assessment and Upgrade Project
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
The UFMS investment consists of the operations and maintenance of the existing UFMS system and projects to enhance the UFMS system including Oracle R12 upgrade assessment and the R12 upgrade (implementation).  This investment is part of HHS’ broader Financial System Improvement Program (FSIP) and supports its Goal 2: Maintain a Secure, Reliable and Efficient Systems Environment.  In addition it supports the objectives of the HHS Chief Financial Officer community and HHS strategic plan. 
 
Oracle’s E-Business Suite environment will become obsolete in December 2015 when Oracle’s exception to the extended support ends.  At that point HHS will stop receiving quarterly patches for UFMS which may impact the security, reliability and availability of these systems and leave the system vulnerable.  The latest version of Oracle Federal Financials (R12) also provides significant functional enhancements that will strengthen HHS’ compliance with Federal Financial Management Improvement Act (FFMIA).  HHS seeks to upgrade UFMS to version R12 in a managed federal cloud/hosting environment through this investment.
SDLC Methodology: 3 - Not Primarily a Software Development Project

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: IHS Health Information Technology Systems and Support
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Transitioning to the International Classification of Disease, 10th Revision (ICD-10) includes the design, programming, testing and implementation of the ASC X12 5010 and NCPDP D.0 transaction sets and the ICD-10 code sets within the Resource and Patient Management System (RPMS).  Design of this project will include the capability of running ICD-9 and ICD-10 in parallel. Strategic management and planning, extensive system changes, specialized education, and effective training and implementation are essential to a successful transition. The process will require the Office of Information Technology (OIT) to significantly modify the RPMS to accommodate the new codes. To this end, training of all staff that utilize ICD-10, including providers, billers, coders and others, will be required to ensure not only an efficient implementation of the code set conversion software, but also an understanding of the documentation requirements and coding guidelines.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: The characteristics of this project require a high degree of interdependency among 30+ application updates to fulfill the requirements set forth by the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid (CMS) mandate for ICD-10 implementation.  The requirements analysis, design, development, and testing of all application changes has been scheduled toward the ultimate goal of a single release date in order to meet the overall requirement of upgrading the entire RPMS system to use ICD-10 diagnosis codes for clinical documentation and billing. All modifications must be tested in an integrated environment and released to users at the same time.  Releasing application changes at earlier or more frequent intervals was not feasible for this project and would have adversely affected the production environments of users and impacted patient care as all modifications were dependent on one another to provide the necessary capabilities required by the mandate.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: NIH NCI Cancer Therapy Evaluation Program (CTEP)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Cancer Therapy Evaluation Program Enterprise System (CTEP-ESYS) is the primary data collection mechanism for the Division of Cancer Treatment and Diagnosis' vast clinical trials program. CTEP-ESYS collects safety and clinical results data on 1,356 ongoing cancer clinical trials (trials not yet completed); of those 1,116 are treatment trials. CTEP-ESYS tracks more than 27,000 patients per year in more than 24 disease areas. The system supports 517,000 drug orders and 37,000 registered investigators. Data reporting and analysis in real time is critical to ensuring adequate monitoring of the ongoing clinical research. Timely data reporting and analysis also assures effective planning for the required successor studies, thus accelerating the evaluation of promising new agents and regimens for patients with cancer. An effective CTEP-ESYS allows investigators and researchers to focus on scientific opportunity, patient safety and reducing the burden of cancer on the public by finding better ways to treat, control and cure cancer. There are many components that support CTEP needs including protocol tracking, agent authorization and tracking, clinical data reporting, adverse event reporting and processing, clinical trials auditing, financial management, investigational new agent and development, disease management and tracking, annual report generation, regulatory activities, account management, investigator registration, reporting and analysis. CTEP-ESYS consist of a common repository that interfaces with suite of applications that are integrated and support the cancer-clinical trials infrastructure.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: NIH NCI Cancer Therapy Evaluation Program (CTEP)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: CTEP-ESYS collects safety and clinical results data for more than 1500 ongoing cancer clinical trials (trials not yet completed) that monitor more than 45,000 patients per year in more than 24 disease areas. Data reporting and analysis in real time is critical to ensuring adequate monitoring of the ongoing clinical research. Timely data reporting and analysis also assures effective planning for the required successor studies, thus accelerating the evaluation of promising new agents and regimens for patients with cancer. An effective CTEP-ESYS allows investigators and researchers to focus on scientific opportunity, patient safety and reducing the burden of cancer on the public by finding better ways to treat, control and cure cancer. There are over 29 integrated components that support CTEP needs including protocol tracking, drug authorization and tracking, clinical data reporting, adverse event reporting and processing, clinical trials auditing, financial management, investigational new drug and disease management and tracking, annual report generation, regulatory activities, account management, investigator registration, reporting and analysis, and more. CTEP-ESYS is an integrated flexible modular user-friendly IT system that supports the cancer-clinical trials infrastructure. CTEP-ESYS includes an effective and well-constructed management tool that mines complex drug, disease and clinical data into meaningful information and knowledge for decision-making. The goals of CTEP-ESYS are to: - Provide reliable clinical results and toxicity data for the largest sponsor of cancer clinical trials in the U.S. - Shift focus from administrative tasks to science - Improve patient/trial safety - Assure the security and confidentially of proprietary and patient information - Eliminate data redundancy throughout the oncology community - Empower staff to make educated decisions by improving access, quality and timeliness of data - Enhance staff efficiency and capabilities - Provide a Cost Effective Approach to Addressing Administrative, Scientific and Regulatory Concerns.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Program Engineering Support includes the GIISST and the ABC Study. The GNSS Intentional Interference and Spoofing Study Team (GIISST) was established by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) Satellite Navigation Program Office and Aircraft Certification Service – Avionic Systems Branch (co-sponsors) to study existing threat assessments, relevant studies and data, and develop specific, actionable recommendations for the FAA with regard to technical, political/legal, and operational mitigations for civil aviation GNSS vulnerabilities to intentional interference and spoofing. The first phase of the ABC effort is to investigate current susceptibility of aviation equipment to base station and handset LTE signals.

Investment Title: FAAXX610: Aviation Safety Knowledge Management Environment (ASKME)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The ASKME Seg2 IDE will replace the four major, independent systems that were originally planned for Segment 2 (Budget Management (BMGMT), Airworthiness Directives Development (ADD), Airworthiness Certification (AC), and Compliance & Enforcement Actions (CEA)). This change in implementation strategy is the result of lessons learned from Segment 1, the recognition of higher risk related to integration of disparate systems, and the identification of a number of common requirements among the systems. The four independent projects have either been stopped or will be stopped before the end of FY14. The Seg2 IDE will first consolidate all of the requirements into a single requirements set, produce a high-level architecture and design, and produce a plan for the development, test, and implementation of the system within existing baseline constraints. The Seg2 IDE replanning process started on 7/2/2014, the consolidated detailed requirements document was signed 4/29/2015, and the JRC approved the replan on 6/17/2015. The deadline to complete the entire system (based on the existing baseline for the four disparate systems) is 9/29/2017.
SDLC Methodology: 3 - Not Primarily a Software Development Project
Release Every Six Mo Comment: Project was stopped 2/8/2016 due to technical issues and has been replaced with the Segment 2 Revised Plan

Investment Title: FAAXX610: Aviation Safety Knowledge Management Environment (ASKME)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Segment 2 - Revised Plan was approved by the Joint Resources Council (JRC) following a Strategy Decision briefing on 9/21/2016. This project replaces the Segment 2 - Integrated Development Effort (IDE) that was stopped on 2/8/2016 due to technical issues. The revised plan will build functionality for Airworthiness Directives Development (ADD), Compliance and Enforcement Actions (CEA), and Airworthiness Certification (AWC). The functionality will be built on the .NET architecture used for ASKME Segment 1 systems, and integration between these systems will be achieved at the data layer and with the use of middleware services. The Budget Management (BMGMT) system will no longer be built since it was discovered that the existing FAA REGIS system provides equivalent functionality.

The DMIS/TROR application is capturing information related to each Federal agency's debt portfolio. It provides a management view of the Federal government's outstanding debt status. The Department of the Treasury uses DMIS/TROR to compile Federal debt collection figures and identify courses of action agencies must take to improve their compliance with the Debt Collection Improvement Act of 1996 (DCIA). Since DMIS/TROR acts as a central repository for DCIA information. It allows the Department of the Treasury a means of measuring compliance and preparing the Debt Collection Annual Report to Congress.

2015 Process and Technology Improvements (PTI) includes major and significant enhancments to FedDebt, Treasury Offset Program and Data Information Repository, all which are Debt Management Services specific applications. These enhancments are expected to improve the Bureau of the Fiscal Service's process in collecting and resolving delinquent debts owed to governmnet agencies.

The Debt Management Information System/Treasury Report On Receivables (DMIS/TROR) application is capturing information related to each Federal agency's debt portfolio. It provides a management view of the Federal governement's outstanding debt status. The Departmenet of the Treausry uses DMIS/TROR to compile Federal debt collection figures and identify courses of action agencies must take to improve their compliance with the Debt Collection Improvement Act of 1996 (DCIA). Since DMIS/TROR acts as a central repository for DCIA information, it allows the Department of the Treausry a means of measuring compliance and preparing the Debt Collection Annual report to Congress.

IDMS-RM (Integrated Document Management-Records Management) provides inbound document receiving and transformation (Esker Document Manager), digital document storage and retreival (IDM) and business process automation (workflow)(OpenText Records & Documents - Vignette Edition) primarily for the Debt Management Service, but also for Payments Management, Judgment Fund Claims and Legislative & Public Affairs (Congressional Correspondence).

The FedDebt system supports Debt Management System (DMS) objectives by providing a comprehensive debt management program. More specifically, the FedDebt system collects delinquent debts due to state and Federal government. The related fees collected generate DMS revenue.

TOPNG (Treasury Offset Program Next Generation) is a centralized offset program for collecting delinquent debts owed to federal agencies and states. Under TOPNG, the Fiscal Service matches a database of delinquent debtors against payments Treasury disburses, then offsets (withholds) federal payments to recipients who owe delinquent debts. The related fees collected generate DMS revenue.

The Call Tracking System (CTS) serves as a central application to the operation of the Treasury Offset Program (TOP) Call Center. It is the primary tool used by call center agents and the IVR to log key call transaction information. CTS helps DMS monitor and evenly distributes incoming call volume in collections centers.
Debt Information Repository (DIR) provides comprehensive information on the status of debt owed the United States. It combines data from FedDebt, TOP, TROR, CRS and CTS systems.

IDMS ((Integrated Database Management System) is a digital imaging system for documents related to the DMS business activites. Enhancements include expanding IDMS-RM functionality for AWG (Administrative Wage Garnishment), increasing efficiency and expanding capacity to handle incoming correspondence and automate transfer of files between DMS, PCAs and Agencies.

Using TOP, Fiscal Service matches a database of delinquent debtors against payments issued by Treasury. With a match, recipients of federal payments who also owe delinquent debts have their payment withheld or reduced to satisfy the debt.

The Cross Servicing Next Generation (CSNG) effort replaces the FedDebt Enterprise System with a COTS product (Ontario Artiva) to improve ability to meet rapidly changing business needs, reduce costs, and improved productivity, as measured by the amount of collections completed, the cost of collections, the number of accounts worked per employee, and the % of fees retained by DMS.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Accounting Operations Branch's (AOB) DPAS Project is a holistic redesign of the DMS Accounting Solution to account for delinquent debt collection.  The DPAS Solution introduces the Debt Information Repository Accounting Database (DIR-AD) as a central accounting hub, which will summarize financial information from program systems, and pass the information to the accounting system.  The solution also encompasses modifying the DMS Systems Architecture, and migrating from Financial Accounting Collections Disbursements and Reporting (FACDR) System to Fiscal Service's Administrative Resource Center (ARC).  The accounting system will be the Oracle Federal Financials on the ARC cloud-based platform.  This project includes all analysis, governance, selection of software, design, and development needed to complete this task.  In addition, it includes all subprojects and initiatives that will have an impact to this project's success.
SDLC Methodology: 3 - Not Primarily a Software Development Project

HR Connect is the core human resource system of the HR Connect Program Office (HRCPO), a shared services center HR service provider within the U.S. Department of Treasury.  The HR Connect application is the foundation of HRCPO's comprehensive suite of solutions and is rapidly becoming the gold standard among federal HR Line of Business (LOB) providers.

HR practitioners, managers and employees use HR Connect (HRC) to perform a wide array of transactions at various stages of an employee's life cycle. HR practitioners use HR Connect to manage human capital and better utilize organizational data for strategic decision making. The system's paperless personnel actions electronically route actions for approval, greatly reducing processing time and the human error associated with manual processing.  Using one of the self-service components of Treasury SSC such as InService, managers can produce recruitment requests as well as requests for personnel actions, such as to promote and award employees.  Managers can also view reports and conduct a range of other  to build, sustain, and manage their team. Employees can make changes to their personal information, view information about their job and benefits, and report their time. As a result, HR practitioners, managers, and employees are partially relieved of cumbersome paperwork and are better able to participate in supporting their agencies' strategic objectives.  

The U.S. Department of Commerce is in the process of consolidating its HR service centers by modeling its business processes within HR Connect and migrating HR data from its seven internal HR servicing bureaus into HR Connect.  They, along with our many other customers, recognize that, in addition to saving time and reducing cost, HR practitioners will be able to spend more time on strategic activities that help meet their agencies' core objectives.  HRCPO systems' robust security ensures the confidentiality, integrity and availability of customer data.  Aside from the core HR connect product, the Department of Commerce will also be leveraging our Workforce Analytics product, with plans to integrate EODS in the near future.

IMF Output analyzes, reformats and extracts taxpayer data received from IMF Posting & Analysis processing to Refunds, Notices, Transcripts, Unpostables, Recap and IDRS processing.  The Refund data is sent to Austin Regional Operating Center (AROC); Notice data is passed to NRPS processing; Transcripts are sent to the Service Centers for printing; Recap reports are sent to the Service Centers; and data extracted for IDRS is sent to the Service Centers.

IMFOL is the Individual Master File On-Line project.  IMFOL is part of the Corporate Files ON-Line (CFOL) system and is used primarily to display tax account information on individual taxpayers to IDRS users.  The database and software provide interfaces to other projects such as ENTCK, National Account Profile/On-Line Entity (NAP/OLE), and Telephone Routing Interactive System (TRIS).  The system is hosted on ECC-MTB's IBM mainframe computer using Customer Information Control System (CICS) as a transaction processor.  The database structure for IMFOL is through the Integrated Data Retrieval System/Security and Communications System (IDRS/SACS) telecommunication and security network. All IMFO programs are written in Assembler Language, COBOL, CICS and execute on the IBM Mainframe at ECC-MTB.

IMF Posting posts transactions for 1040 filers, reconcile debits and credits, update status, compute and assess/abate penalties and interest.  IMF Analysis programs analyze individual accounts, performs issue detection, and analyze for subsequent action, notices, refunds, etc.
IMF Pre-Posting project reformats tax forms and transactions, and performs preliminary checks and validation, before passing them to the IMF.

IMFDIF is a mathematical technique used to pre-classify and identify a return's high audit potential.  All individual returns are DIF scored but only those above the cut-off are placed onto inventories and made available to Examination field personnel for selection.  Returns can either be selected specifically via a TC424 or bulk ordered via an ordering system.  These accounts provide significant workload for field Examination personnel.

The Federal Student Aid – Datashare (FSA-D) is an English and Spanish web based application which provides taxpayers completing the "Free Application For Student Aid (FAFSA)" through the Department of Education’s (ED)’s "FAFSA On The Web (FOTW)" with access to relevant tax data from their filed individual Federal tax return. FOTW provides the sole means of taxpayer access to the FSA-D. The FSA-D delivers to an authenticated taxpayer’s web browser his or her relevant federal tax information in real time.  In addition, implement Income Based-Repayment (IBR) Status functionality for FSA.

eTranscript/Send My Transcript comprises web and phone applications which provide taxpayers with readily accessible, clear, up-to-date and accurate tax-related information.  The eTranscript/Send My Transcript  Web Application will provide taxpayers a means to electronically send their tax transcript to the secure "mailbox" of a third party, typically a prospective lender.

A Phone and Web based application to allow a taxpayer to check the status of their 1040X return and to shift taxpayer traffic from Customer Service Representatives to an automated self-service application.  The product will be available in both English and Spanish.

Get Transcript is an online service that provides a time saving and cost effective way to directly obtain one or more available transcripts for a prior four tax year.  Taxpayers can view, print and download these documents in a PDF through IRS website. Using this web application, taxpayers can request their Return, Record of Account, Account, and Proof of Non-Filing transcripts for a four year period.  In addition, using this web interface, taxpayers can request Wage & Income documents for the last ten years.
Updates and Enhancements to applications under the ICCE investment.

Combine the IRS legacy Personal Identification Number (PIN) solutions for individual taxpayer filing (IMF) into a consolidated solution for 2014 and future years.  The eventual goal is to have one PIN for individual taxpayers in 2015 and beyond to facilitate electronic tax return filing (e-File) and to protect tax payer accounts against identity theft.

The aim of this solution is to drive taxpayers to get a legacy Identity Protection (IP) PIN (proposed new name Taxpayer Filing Authentication Certificate [TFAC]) to protect their accounts and to facilitate e-Filing.  In order to receive a TFAC a taxpayer would have authenticate using the IRS e-Authentication (e-Auth) solution that leverage third-party out-of-wallet (OOW) data.  The legacy e-File PIN (EFP) would only be issued to taxpayers that cannot authentication with e-Auth (but can authenticate with legacy methods) to e-File.  Taxpayers issued a legacy e-File PIN would be subject to additional filters and reviews when they file their tax returns.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: DCPS is a Commissioner's priority initiative to replace the 52 disparate Disability Determination (DD) components systems, support, and maintenance processes with a modern, common case-processing system. DCPS will transition the DD components from 52 fragmented, highly customized legacy systems to a common system that uses automated tools and leverages current technology.  DCPS will benefit SSA's disability process functionally and technologically by providing full process integration, ease of sharing disability processing workload across DD Component sites, a common interface with other SSA offices and systems, and a dramatic reduction in the technological complexity of system support. Once fully operational, DCPS will deliver common functionality and consistent support to each DD Component, while providing accurate, current, consistent, and accessible data for national consumption; leading to enhanced anti-fraud efforts, as well as enhancing the agency’s IT security posture through greater visibility and accountability.  DCPS will integrate the entire claims process from start to finish, including case processing, correspondence, fiscal, management information, and workload management.  The system will use electronic case analysis to support disability examiners in making consistent decisions based on SSA Disability Policy, and leverage SSA's investment in Intelligent Disability.    It will provide a disability vendor repository that consolidates existing DD Component vendor data stores, which can then be utilized by all the disability case processing partners nationwide (e.g., Field Offices, DDSs, and Hearing Offices).  DCPS will provide SSA Disability Policy consistency, compliance, and flexibility as we are able to implement policy changes more readily to keep pace with changes in the environment.  Replacing the current DD component systems with DCPS will minimize the average processing time for initial disability claims, decrease case processing-related task time and provide increased system availability to improve the overall quality of the disability determination process. This supports the agency's strategic goal to Improve the Way We Do Business through the strategy to Modernize Disability Case Processing.

Project Name: Integrated Data Retrieval System (IDRS) - Filing Season 2012
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Development for legislatively mandated tax law changes (for example, portions of Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act) and customer requested modernization and enhancement (for example, accelerate processing cycle)  * The Integrated Data Retrieval System (IDRS) is an IRS mission critical system consisting of databases and subsystems supporting IRS employees working active tax cases. It manages data retrieved from the Tax Master Files allowing IRS employees to take specific actions on taxpayer account issues, track status and post updates back to the Master Files. It provides for systemic review of case status, alleviating staffing needs and providing consistency in case control. Actions taken via IDRS include notice issuance, installment agreement processing, offers in compromise, adjustment processing, penalty and interest computations and explanations, credit and debit transfers within an account or other related accounts and research of taxpayer accounts for problem resolution of taxpayer inquiries.

Agency Name: Department of Housing and Urban Development
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
The New Core Program is a multi-phase effort to modernize HUD's core financial and key administrative systems by transitioning the system functions to a shared services environment. New Core’s first phase will migrate financial management and administrative functions to the Department of Treasury, Bureau of Fiscal Services, Administrative Resource Center's (ARC) shared services platform through multiple releases. 

Release 1 will allow HUD to migrate from the current e-Gov Travel Service 1 contract provider, FedTraveler, to the e-Gov Travel Service 2 contractor provider, Concur Government Edition, utilizing ARC for travel service administration.  This transition is required to meet Federal GSA e-Travel Service 2 requirements. Additionally, HUD will migrate to ARC's MoveLinq will allow HUD to retire contracts for HUD operated MoveLinq in late FY 2015.  This will also include migration to ARC's Oracle Federal Financials for travel and relocation accounting.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: The New Core Project is being broken out into smaller projects which represent three currently planned releases.

Agency Name: Department of Housing and Urban Development
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Release 2 will allow HUD to migrate from HUD's Web Time and Attendance System to  an ARC managed, integrated time and attendance system that supports payroll processing. Implementation of ARC's WebTA will provide the framework to implement Managerial Cost Accounting, providing detailed cost information to aid daily management decisions.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: The New Core Project is being broken out into smaller projects which represent three currently planned releases.

Agency Name: Department of Housing and Urban Development
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Release 3 will transfer functionality associated with budgeting, accounting, financial management, Federal reporting, and procurement to ARC managed Oracle Federal Financials system and PRISM system. This will provide HUD with an integrated core financial system intended to increase accuracy, speed, transparency, and accountability in financial management and budgeting for the agency, allow HUD to quickly accommodate legislative changes in its financial system, and make high-quality data available to support managerial decision-making to deliver HUD's mission.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: The New Core Project is being broken out into smaller projects which represent three currently planned releases.

Agency Name: Department of Housing and Urban Development
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: HUD utilized the Treasury Pay.gov service to support all financial transactions between HUD and the user community.  Treasury Pay.gov services is moving to a new security platform and will be decommissioning the legacy platform in FY16.  HUD is developing a common service to connect all systems that need to transition to the new platform which will allow for a enterprise solution to support the transactions.

Agency Name: Department of Housing and Urban Development
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The FHA Transformation Initiative’s goal is to leverage a modern  information technology platform to better manage and mitigate risk across all of FHA’s Insurance Programs.  Specifically, FHA Transformation will enable risk detection and fraud prevention by capturing critical data points at the front-end of the loan life cycle and leveraging the industry standard risk and fraud tools and services, rules-based technology, and transactional controls to minimize exposure to FHA’s Insurance Funds. Agency Name: Department of Housing and Urban Development
Project Name: Re-engineer Integrated Disbursement Information System (IDIS) To Remove First-In-First-Out (FIFO)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: IDIS manages the fund disbursement rules for thousands of grantees and sub recipients totaling approximately $5 billion annually in program funds. Beginning FY14 IDIS will require a fundamental change to the processing and attribution of grant year funds to individual disbursement events, away from the "first-in-first-out" (FIFO) method toward funds disbursements confined specifically to the grant year for which an activity is set-up by the grantee. This activity is a Deputy Secretary priority and will ensure IDIS system compliance to Federal Financial Management Improvement Act (FFMIA). This DME activity eliminates CPD’s contribution to the qualified opinion for HUD's FY13 Financial Statement.

This initiative aligns with the Office of Management and Budget (OMB) M13-08, Improving Financial Systems through Shared Services and supports the VA’s strategic objective to “Enhance Productivity and Improve the Efficiency of the Provision of Veteran Benefits and Services.” The FMBT initiative will securely enhance the VA’s ability to plan and execute its budget, pay Veterans accurately and efficiently, pay vendors, and produce accurate financial statements. Taxpayers and employees benefit from a transparent, accurate, timely, reliable financial information system.The FMBT program modernizes VA’s financial management system and the interfaces feeding into it. The new system will support automating internal controls and reduce audit issues; standardize, integrate, automate, and streamline financial management business processes, shift the administrative burden to the system, and enhance leadership decision-making through analytics and ensure compliance with Federal Financial Management Improvement Act (FFMIA) and other regulatory requirements.

Release Every Six Mo Comment: EDFacts is primarily operations; we schedule DME activities to avoid disrupting operations and to level resources.  DME work is performed discontinuously if required to meet the operations schedule. DME work may also be rescheduled if operational requirements change.  For example, new Secretarial initiatives that may arise during the year have priority over DME activities.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The goal of EDFacts Modernization is to implement the selected alternative, Push-Pull, a complete redesign distinguished by a 21st century approach to collecting K-12 education data. It is assumed a private K-12 cloud (a hybrid with a minimum of federal, state, and third party entities) will be formed and an organization such as SIFA or CCSSO will assume the role of data aggregator that includes accepting and providing federal reporting data to EDFacts. Similar to the Common Education Data Standards (CEDS) initiative, ED would take the lead to control requirements and development to ensure the cloud is vetted by the federal government. If the development of a K-12 cloud takes longer than expected, the push/pull solution would be implemented using other cloud hosting, eventually moving to the K-12 cloud. EMAPS is the pilot application that moves to the cloud, testing changes needed to move remaining EDFacts applications to the cloud. EDFacts functions will be re-architected into an integrated application, starting with redesign of the data model. Three main EDFacts components are envisioned in the redesigned system: Data provider, data storage, and data usage applications. Redesign ensures EDFacts will work efficiently and effectively in the cloud. Design considerations include upgrading applications so that user interfaces are cohesive, consistent, and up-to-date, integrating both single-sign-on and eventually social media.
Update system infrastructure so there is support (currently is obsolete and there is no more support).
SDLC Methodology: 3 - Not Primarily a Software Development Project

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The GWA/TRS Project will provide the functionality to enter Classification Key (C-Key) for check processing to support Government Wide accounting implementation in OTCnet project. Providing the information at detail check level will be mandatory for Agencies that are marked as "GWA Reporter".  The release includes sending the information to TRS for the first time for check processing using XML Schema v4.6. Deposit processing side of OTCnet transmission to TRS will also be revised to use XML v4.6 schema. Interface specifications will be updated and tested for 3 interfaces including DECA, IRS and DDS systems.

Corrections and Adjustments project will provide the functionality to process Corrections and Adjustments in OTCnet. Corrections and Adjustments for checks will be processed from Debit Gateway to OTCnet and will be reported to TRS. For deposit processing, a user interface will be designed to enter the information into OTCnet and then transmit the information to TRS. Following the scope discussions, this project was cancelled in Feb. 2012.

This project has been postponed to a later date due to re-prioritization. The project was planned to provide dynamic split functionality to agencies for check processing and transmitting the data to TRS and the Central Accounting and Reporting System (CARS).  Agencies have expressed the need to be able to enter C-Key information at summary level for end of day processing for checks.  In the absence of the dynamic split functionality in OTCnet, agencies will have to use bulk reclassification process in GWA which will require agencies to reconcile between two different systems.

Straight through Processing (STP) is a Treasury mandate to provide immediate recording of transactions and near real-time information for reconciliation and management of the Treasury's General Account (TGA) structure. The OTCnet STP implementation will be in two different segments due to immediate and long-term needs. 

The first implementation of STP in near term will require processing the appropriate Treasury RTNs for checks and deposit processing, processing a new Treasury RTN for Non-Appropriated Funds (NAF), voucher date change and sending it to Collections Information Repository (CIR).  The implementation will be closely coordinated with the Debit Gateway and CIR.  For commercial deposits, a new Treasury RTN will be defined for cash concentration and processed through CIR to Treasury Cash Management System (TCMS). 

The second implementation of STP will include processing of Adjustment/Correction and Rescinds (ACRs) for checks,, using XML 4.6 schema as standard interface and processing the of end-of-day file from Debit Gateway.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: Currently OTCnet does not have a production release scheduled every six months. However, the OTCnet team is in the planning phase to implement a release schedule, which will include a production release every six months.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Archive and Architecture Phase 1 will introduce a check transactional data archival process to improve OTCnet application performance and adhere to Fiscal Service' Data Retention Requirements.  Architecture Phase 1 will include breaking up operational  Online Transaction Processing (OLTP) database and the Archive database into two databases and defining an archive process.  The operational database will hold 18 months of current financial transactions and the archive database containing all historical information.  A new archive process will be defined to move data from operational database to the archive database. Modifications will be made for check search functionality and reports .  Additional architectural changes include converting batch jobs from Hibernate to Spring Batch framework. During phase 1, the archiving process will be limited to check processing only.  Archiving Phase 2 will include expanding archiving to deposit processing and adding additional reports from archive data.  Also, Hibernate optimization will be completed to move away from JBPM and use Spring Batch Framework where inefficiencies exist.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: Currently OTCnet does not have a production release scheduled every six months. However, the OTCnet team is in the planning phase to implement a release schedule, which will include a production release every six months.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: A system rewrite of TAAPS will begin in October 2011 with the first phase being define and documentation.  The rewrite may improve auction screens, reports, interfaces, or infrastructure to provide timely, accurate, and informative qualitative/quantitative analysis of Treasury Auctions.  Phase two will be the development phase and move towards the implementation process of the rewrite. Planned implementation of 9/30/2013.

In 2011, Treasury conducted 269 marketable security auctions to borrow the monies needed to fund the United States Government. The auction process must work flawlessly, remain absolutely secure, and operate without service disruptions which could erode public confidence and increase taxpayer costs for debt service.
 
The Treasury Automated Auction Processing System (TAAPS) application and infrastructure have been in production for four years and in development for two years prior to that. In order to stay current with changes in technology, it is prudent to examine various components of the auction process to analyze the validity and adequacy of the utilized technology, application and infrastructure.  

The business process components being analyzed have been organized into 8 areas of focus:
1. Infrastructure & Security
2. Credential Management
3. Operational Efficiencies
4. Internal Staff Recommendations
5. External Participant Feedback
6. Data Analytics
7. Customer Relationship Management
8. Institutional Website Revamp.

The Savings Bond Redemption System (SABRS) is used to process the redemption of accrual U.S. savings bonds held in paper form and to perform the resulting taxable reporting functions.  In a typical year, Retail processes the redemption of over one million bonds worth more than $1 billion using SABRS.

The current SABRS is built on dated technology that will reach the end of its supportable life in July 2019.  The continued use of this application will jeopardize Retail's ability to both make timely and accurate payments to investors and ensure timely and accurate reporting of federal tax information, which are mission essential functions for the program.  The end of supportable life issue for the current application would introduce potential security vulnerabilities.

Consequently, Retail has obtained approval from the Investment Review Board (IRB) to initiate a project to develop and deploy a more technologically current and viable replacement for SABRS.  The IRB gave initial approval to explore the concept of building a replacement on 09-11-2017.  The FS Technical Architectural Review Board (TARB) approved the proposed design on 04-02-2018, and the IRB authorized the project to proceed on 05-07-2018.

Replacing the current technologically dated application is expect to yield savings in operations and maintenance cost.  Based on the current 5-year Period of Performance (PoP) Retail anticipates a net reduction of $0.955 million (the net reduction in O&M cost of $2.564 less the project's development cost $1.609 million).

The purpose of this BCR is to add this new project into the RSS investment’s baseline.

Project Name: Operations & Systems Modernization/Systems Modernization:  Rewrite the Savings Bond Redemption System (SABRS)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
The Savings Bond Redemption System (SABRS) is used to process the redemption of accrual U.S. savings bonds held in paper form.  In a typical year, Retail processes the redemption of over one million bonds worth more than $1 billion using SABRS.

The current SABRS is built on dated technology that will reach the end of its supportable life in late 2019.  The continued use of this application will jeopardize Retail's ability to both make timely and accurate payments to investors, which is a mission essential functions for the program.  The end of supportable life issue for the current application would also introduce potential security vulnerabilities.  This project will develop a more technologically current and sustainable application to replace the existing system, which will be hosted and maintained on a cloud environment.

Due to these factors, all components of the system must be deployed in concert to ensure that a useable application is implemented.

CJIS Information Broker Study.

The CJIS Information Broker (CIB) addresses an FBI Criminal Justice Information Services (CJIS) Division initiative for
providing innovative methods for exchanging, timely, accurate, and relevant criminal justice information with Federal,
State, Tribal and Local law enforcement agencies (LEAs), as well as criminal justice agencies (CJAs) worldwide. The
initiative is a solution for satisfying the needs and requirements of the CJIS stakeholder community, both internal and
external to CJIS, by providing a tool that will improve CJIS's process performance, enhance technical capabilities for
sharing information, reduce turnaround time for CJIS products and special requests for information, divert lower
priority "reporting traffic away from mission critical systems, and reduce operation costs.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: For FY16, the CIB activity will be cancelled with the exception of O&M costs for the functionality that has previously been delivered.

Project Name: Single Trade Application and Reporting System (STARS)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
Let's Export is a single portal website to all export activities.  This portal was created in support of the President's Export Control Reform (ECR) Initiative.  The goal of this website is to establish a single location for all U.S. export licensing systems and to better assist new users to the export community on how and where to begin.

The service will provide a single portal that incorporates functionality from the following separate agency systems:

State's DTrade is a fully electronic system in which registered users may submit permanent exports and temporary exports and import applications and amendments for defense articles and services.

Commerce's SNAP-R allows users to submit export license applications, commodity classification requests, encryption registration, reexport license applications, and license exception AGR notifications.

Treasury's OFAC: Applications to exports pursuant to the Trade Sanctions Reform and Export Enhancement Act of 2000.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: Agile process to develop functionality and incrementally release finished capabilities to the users.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: CDC National Center for Emerging and Zoonotic Diseases NHSN Systems
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The National Healthcare Safety Network (NHSN) is a web-based information system designed for use by CDC and partners as a resource for surveillance and improvement of patient and healthcare personnel safety. The principal goals of NHSN are to improve safety by creating and disseminating knowledge necessary to detect and respond to current and emerging healthcare safety threats. The development aspects of the project primarily supports and maintain the operations of the system and integrates new feature and functionality as deemed necessary by CDC’s Division of Healthcare Quality Promotion program.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Fraud Prevention System (FPS) analyzes data from several systems from across the Medicare business lifecycle. FPS plays a central role in the overall program integrity strategy of the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS). FPS uses data from multiple claims and non-claims data sources in order to identify potential fraud, waste, and abuse. FPS supports pre-payment edits to stop claims payment or trigger other oversight processes, to improve fraud deterrence and prevention. FPS makes use of information from all parts of the service chain and other data to apply fraud detection models. FPS is currently integrated with Unified Case Management (UCM) using bi-directional webservices replacing the previous file sharing approach and supports monitoring of fraud activities through the end of the fraud lifecycle to support program reporting.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The CMS developed and implemented the FPS2 to apply predictive analytics technologies to identify and prevent the payment of fraudulent claims in the Medicare FFS Program, as required by the Small Business Jobs Act of 2010.  The FPS2 plays a central role in the overall program integrity strategy and uses data from multiple claims and non-claims data sources in order to identify potential fraud, waste, and abuse. The FPS2 supports Edits to stop claims payment or trigger other oversight processes, to improve fraud deterrence and prevention. The FPS2 also performs analysis on claims, applying predictive Models and other algorithms to identify providers/suppliers exhibiting a pattern of behavior that is indicative of potential fraud, waste and abuse, to generate alerts of potentially fraudulent providers for further investigation.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The STC has four scheduled (January, April, July and October) quarterly releases that control, implement, and update the software due to legislative mandates that dictate the amount of payment for services or coverage levels.  TheSTC also implements changes needed to support the Medicare Administrative Contractors (MACs) authority for the Medicare FFS Program.  Software changes for the claims processing operations are managed in quarterly releases developed through a change control process that begins with the Medicare Change Control Board (MCCB) review and prioritization of pending requests.  The FFS Operations Board approves the quarterly releases with oversight by the FFS Governance Council and manages/integrates day-to-day operations of the FFS program across CMS.  Error-free releases that implement legislative mandates with minimal interruption to processing ensure that beneficiaries receive the correct service and providers receive the correct payment.

Project Name: Modernized TECS Operational at the Second Data Center (DC2)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
This milestone is defined as having a second instance of the CBP modernized TECS system being operable at a second data center. The second data center is currently planned to be DHS Data Center 2 (DC2). The capability associated with achieving this milestone is focused on replicating mission-critical TECS user interface functionality, making it possible to have switchover capability during TECS system maintenance and for unscheduled outages. Achieving this capability also establishes a disaster recovery (DR) site as well as a Continuity of Operations (COOP) capability that greatly enhances current capability. 
 
Being able to switch operations between data centers establishes the ability to continue using mission critical functions without the limitations experienced with legacy TECS during planned maintenance or unplanned outages. This closes a longstanding capability gap. The lessons learned and results from DC2 Milestone will allow CBP to fully assess emerging cloud technology, and determine if the replication of less critical functions should be established at DC2 or onto the cloud technology, which may reduce or replace reliance on brick and mortar data center infrastructures.
SDLC Methodology: 3 - Not Primarily a Software Development Project
Release Every Six Mo Comment: This is a Data Center Migration project, not a software development project. There is no production release.

Investment Title: CBP - Remote Video Surveillance System (RVSS) Upgrade Program
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
Objective: Deploy new Remote Video Surveillance System (RVSS) technology to increase and enhance border surveillance coverage along the Southwest border. 
 
Goal: Complete deployment of the RVSS technology within a Tier 1 Schedule (less than 2 years from approval to proceed) using re-locatable towers. Towers will be deployed on previously disturbed land that will require limited environmental clearance action (Categorical Exclusion) and real estate licenses to reduce the deployment timeline.  The program will provide new surveillance technology coupled with a digital system necessary for Certification & Accreditation, and command and control (C2) facilities to incorporate additional situational awareness capabilities. 
 
Current and Expected Outcomes: Persistence Surveillance along the Southwest Border by increased situational awareness due to the added range of cameras systems, video analytics and upgraded Command and Control (C2).

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The objectives of the EDW 2.xx project are to deploy additional functionality and data through new data integrations, enhancements to existing dashboards, and building new dashboards and reports. Improving the functionality, increasing the data, and enhancing the reporting capabilities enables the DoS to move closer toward becoming a data-driven environment which utilizes data to make informed decisions and values the data the organization generates, uses, and shares as an enterprise asset.

The Enterprise Metadata Repository is the centralized repository for the authoritative reference for definition, sources, and use of DoS meta data. The implementation of EMR facilitates re-use of existing data structures, identifies authoritative sorces and stewards of data, shows relationships of data used, and provides end-to-end lineage of data used across DoS.  The EMR can facilitate the implementation of data standards, while highlighting the impact of changes to data, resulting in better understanding of data used throughout DoS.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: CMS MACBIS (Medicaid & CHIP Business Information and Solutions)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
About MACPro: 
Medicaid, authorized by Title XIX of the Social Security Act, and CHIP, reauthorized by the Children’s Health Insurance Program Reauthorization Act of 2009 (CHIPRA) signed into law on February 4, 2009, play an important role in financing health care for approximately 48 million people throughout the country. By 2014, it is expected that an additional 16 million people will become eligible for Medicaid and CHIP as a result of the Affordable Care Act (Public Law 111-148 – Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act). In order to implement the statute, CMS must provide for a mechanism to ensure timely approval of Medicaid and CHIP state plans, waivers and demonstrations and provide for a repository for all Medicaid and CHIP program that supplies data to populate Healthcare.gov (sec. 1103) as well as other required reports. With these tremendous statutory changes in the Medicaid and CHIP programs, CMS will undergo a transformation from a reactive, mostly paper based processing entity to an active, electronic based program manager by automating and streamlining the current systems and processes.

About T-MSIS:
The Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) implemented the T-MSIS initiative in an effort to receive more complete and timely Medicaid and Children’s Health Insurance Programs (CHIP) related data from states. This initiative seeks to reduce the burden on states of multiple requests for data, allowing states to better perform its responsibilities of Medicaid and CHIP program oversight, administration, and program integrity.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: CMS MACBIS (Medicaid & CHIP Business Information and Solutions)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
The Medicaid and CHIP Program (MACPro) system will improve through automation  State Plan Amendment (SPA), Quality Measure Reporting, Waivers (proposals and demonstrations), Advance Planning Documents (APD) (submission and review process

Goals of MACPro:

–      Reduce state/federal burden

–      Improve federal oversight

–      Increase public transparency

–      To improve the state application and federal review processes, federal program management, and transparency.

–      To support data-driven decision making through online access to data and information on Medicaid and CHIP eligibility and programs.

–      Business reengineering around the newly structured program data reducing duplication of functions. 

–      Improved program oversight with the ability to integrate and monitor structured program data with operational data.

  This web-based system will automate the efforts of CMS and will significantly reduce the inconsistencies and disparities between States’ submissions of Medicaid and CHIP program data to CMS and support the larger MACBIS data strategy.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: CMS MACBIS (Medicaid & CHIP Business Information and Solutions)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
The purpose of this requirement is to acquire comprehensive digital service delivery capacity to assist the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) in an effort to continue sustaining and improving the Transformed-Medicaid Statistical Information System (T-MSIS). T-MSIS should remain stable as it evolves to provide continuously improving support for the collection of data for States and Territories. Stability is required for both currently participating States and Territories, as well as new States that join, bringing new types of data. To the greatest extent possible, the system should easily and automatically collect and normalize disparate data resulting in standardized quality data - despite the introduction of new data sources. The following objectives will be met by TMSIS:
1. Maximize the level of automation to produce stable and consistent data quality.
2. Reduce and/or eliminate data anomalies.
3. Provide effective support of onboarding new states/territories.
4. Minimize manual costs, data loss and data corruption.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: CMS MACBIS (Medicaid & CHIP Business Information and Solutions)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: In order to enable administration of the Medicaid Drug Rebate Program (MDRP), MDP will replace 2 systems, the Medicaid Drug Rebate (MDR) and Drug Data Reporting (DDR) system, and the Federal Upper Limit (FUL) process. The merger and enhancement of the MDR, DDR, and FUL responds to evolving technical requirements, out-of-date technology, and new legislative requirements. The new MDP system would incorporate into a single, CMS hosted system, the data collection needs (absorbing the DDR system), drug rebate quarterly unit rebate amounts, quarterly unit rebate offset amounts, and operational needs (absorbing the MDR system) and calculation of the federal upper payment limits for certain therapeutically equivalent drugs (absorbing the FUL process). The new system will also allow the agency to more fully participate in government-wide efforts to provide more detailed and better information to all stakeholders. These changes are expected to significantly enhance operational effectiveness and efficiency.

FIT recently completed a blueprint for financial management shared services.  The blueprint recommends a shared service approach whereby all Federal agencies migrate to one of several designated Federal and private financial management shared service providers (SSP) that offer, at a minimum, a common set of financial management services and products.  Further, the approach includes a lifecycle approval step where FIT reviews and compares an agency's migration proposal to the common services and products to verify the following:  (1) the agency's needs align with the common services and products; (2) the agency can offer support (e.g., regulatory, statutory) for any needs beyond the common services and products; and (3) any verified Services and Products gaps can be satisfied by one of the designated SSPs.  Once an agency has an acceptable modernization plan, it will begin a brief "discovery" phase with an SSP process whereby both organizations must agree that the services and products offered by the SSP satisfy the needs of the agency.

FIT has developed a series of financial management measures (e.g., price per invoice, on-time payments, discounts and interest paid) to capture the price and performance of a number of financial management processes (e.g., procure-to-pay, bill-to-collect) provided by Federal SSPs.  FIT captures and aggregates the measures reported by the SSPs in a reporting tool (or "benchmarking tool") that aggregates the information as a government-wide benchmark.  FIT, Federal SSPs, and Federal agencies can use the benchmarking tool to compare the cost and performance of the Federal agencies financial management activities to the price and performance of the Federal SSPs.  The benchmarking tool is a web-based application with defined metrics based on seven financial management end-to-end business processes, including Procure-to-Pay and Bill-to-Collect.  The metrics are based on the price and performance of the aligned business processes of the Federal SSPs.  Examples of the metrics include price per invoice, statement of differences, on- time payments, discounts and interest paid.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Sample Survey Operations support IES's mission to provide national leadership in expanding fundamental knowledge and understanding of education from early childhood through postsecondary study. A significant component of the Institute’s independent research activity relies upon data gathered via sample surveys; that is, surveys (or assessments) of a scientifically-selected sample comprised of individual students or schools from the population of interest. The Sample Survey Operations project includes pre-production, production, and post-production activities that subsume tasks related to (a) sampling and instrumentation development; (b) tracing, locating, and interviewing; and (c) editing, weighting, imputation, and data file development, respectively.

Dissemination Operations support IES's mission to provide parents, educators, students, researchers, policymakers, and the general public with reliable information about the condition and progress of education in the United States, including early childhood education; educational practices that support learning and improve academic achievement and access to educational opportunities for all students; and the effectiveness of Federal and other education programs. The Dissemination Operations project includes activities that subsume tasks related to (a) needs analysis, requirements development, and analysis of alternatives for a wide range of dissemination options ranging from web-based tools to online publications; (b) development, technical review, and release of dissemination products; and (c) dissemination product maintenance.
