Objectives / Expected Outcomes: FY2019 Data Tools and Training Modules project activities support IES's mission to provide parents, educators, students, researchers, policymakers, and the general public with reliable information about the condition and progress of education in the United States, including early childhood education; educational practices that support learning and improve academic achievement and access to educational opportunities for all students; and the effectiveness of Federal and other education programs. The FY2019 Data Tools and Training Modules project objective is to disseminate data via publicly-facing web tools, analytic reports, and public-use and restricted-use micro-level data products.  Subtasks include analysis, requirements development, and analysis of alternatives for a wide range of dissemination options ranging from web-based data tools, web-based training tools, and web publications; application development, technical review, and online release of data; and maintenance of online tools and web pages/data. Key deliverables include datasets added to the DATALAB (PowerStats, QuickStats, etc.) web tool and new/updated modules to the Distance Learning Dataset Training (DLDT) web application.

FY2019 Survey Collection and Analysis activities support IES's mission to provide national leadership in expanding fundamental knowledge and understanding of education from early childhood through postsecondary study. A significant component of the Institute’s independent research activity relies upon data gathered via sample surveys; that is, surveys (or assessments) of a scientifically-selected sample comprised of individual students or schools from the population of interest. The project objectives of the FY2019 Survey Collection and Analysis activities are to (a) collect data from students, families, and elementary, secondary, and postsecondary institutions; (b) securely store those data in accordance with applicable laws, regulations and policies guiding their collection; and (c) facilitate the review, editing, processing of that data by Department of Education staff and authorized contractors. Key deliverables include the successful collection of data via web-based instruments and the accurate analysis of that data.
SDLC Methodology: 3 - Not Primarily a Software Development Project

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
Interactions between medicine and industry have a wide spectrum of purposes and resulting impacts. Collaboration may promote discovery and development of new technologies that improve individual and public health. However, financial ties may create conflicts of interest in other aspects of medicine: clinical practice, clinical and basic science research, medical education, standard setting, and medical publications.
Applicable manufacturers and group purchasing organizations (GPOs) must begin collection of all applicable transfers of value starting on August 1, 2013 and must report the data to CMS and attest to the data on an annual basis thereafter. After a formal data review and dispute process by the covered recipients and submission of corrections by the applicable manufacturers and GPOs, CMS must publish the data on a public website. Data must be published in a way that it is easy to use, is searchable, can be aggregated, and is downloadable.
Manufacturers who produce any drugs, devices, biologicals, or medical supplies covered under Medicare, Medicaid, or the Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP) are subject to Open Payments reporting requirements. Except in special circumstances outlined in the Final Rule, applicable manufacturers and GPOs must disclose and attest to all applicable transactions (payments, other transfers of value, investment interests, etc.) made to any covered recipients, regardless of whether the transfer of value was related to a covered product.
CMS anticipates that patients, physicians, manufacturers, GPOs, third party commercial services, the press, academic researchers, other researchers, and the general public will utilize the data collected by this program.

Project Name: FDA CDER IDM VI - Enhancements & Testing
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
The objective of Integrity VI is to extend and expand the existing Integrity capability to support new business requirements for established master data domains and perform end-to-end integration testing across the CDER Informatics platform as well as legacy CDER systems.  Specifically:
-Master Data Enhancements
- Enhance Product and Product Dictionary (PPD) master data
- Enhance Facility, Site and Supply Chain (FSC) master data
- Enhance Application, Submission, Sponsor and Responsible Organization (ASSO) master   data
- Enhance SPL validation modules
- Enhance the integration between Integrity and other CDER Informatics platform capabilities and legacy CDER systems
- Provide End-to-End Testing
- Conduct end-to-end planning, script development and testing across CDER Informatics platform capabilities.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Project Name: FDA CDER IDM V - Event Data Management
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The goal of Integrity V is to extend and expand the existing Integrity capability to support industry-submitted and FDA-generated event data (aka Event Data Management, EDM) in order to provide integrated submissions and data management for the Drug Safety and Pharmaceutical Quality platforms. Currently, industry-submitted event data to FDA / CDER are scattered among many systems & repositories and included many different types of data formats.  Integrity V will establish a cloud-based data repository and portal to provide a common access point for industry to interact with the FDA.

Web Applications Release 1 will include the development of Online Account, eAuthentication, Authorization Framework, and Mobile.  The release will deliver the following functionality: 

View Account Home Page
  •Enablestaxpayer to view Account Snapshot (Landing) Page
View/Download Tax Return Data Records
  •Enablestaxpayers to view and download tax return (RECORD). Such as: Total exemptions,AGI,Deductions,Taxes due,Payments made,reported on tax return,Balance due: reported per computer,reported on return,Filing status (not fact of filing).  This is a text, pdf or XML version of a tax return; text to view, XML to download
View Balance due including penalties and interest
  •Taxpayer is able to view their balance on their online account so they are aware of any payment responsibilities. This may include anyprincipal, interest, or penalties due
Log into Online Account and Make aPayment from his/her bank account
  •Taxpayerlogs into online Account (using Authorization Framework and eAuth services) and can make a payment (using digital payment options) which in Phase A will be via an integrated payments from his/her bank account
  •Payment confirmation will be offered via email through the API (delivery dependent of Fiscal Services)
View Payment Status & History by tax module
  •Taxpayer can view payment Status and History by tax module (a record of tax data for a specific taxpayer covering only one tax period)
  •Includes:Pending Payments (which requires API from fiscal service), Scheduled CDIA (credit debit installment agreement) payments, capability to modify or cancel payments that were scheduled using the integrated payments capability
  •Taxpayerwill view tax Return Summary (landing Page) for current and previous tax modules.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Enforce 3 system provides support to Border Patrol Agents and CBP Officers through a variety of modules. These modules support agents and officers throughout the various workflow stages of their daily intelligence tracking, apprehension, and enforcement activities. The modules include e3Processing (including Intake and Detentions), e3 Biometrics, e3 Assaults, Federated Person Query (FPQ), e3 Prosecutions, and e3 OASISS. The latter two modules are used by a sub-set of specialized units within the USBP and Office of Field Operations (OFO) to track and manage cases for enforcement programs. The purpose/objective of e3 is to provide a single-entry option for agents to report enforcement incidents, and to collect and process information for reporting measures on the mission, goals, and priorities established by DHS.

The Enterprise Geospatial Information System (eGIS) Program provides CBP personnel with enterprise level geospatial services. These services support personnel in allowing for the creation, searching and accessing of maps and geographic location datasets within a role based administration system. They include the eGIS Map Viewer, Universal Location Point Selector, Portal Application and REST/KML services. The program has expanded with the goal of providing services to other DHS component offices, such as ICE and USCG. The objective of eGIS is to provide situational awareness to all levels of CBP via geographic mapping systems with near real-time information necessary to secure our borders and support the CBP mission.

The ICAD system is the current U.S. Border Patrol command and control system supporting real-time border surveillance and monitoring of agent activity/officer safety. The system identifies and classifies intrusion events from surveillance resources including fielded sensors. The objective of ICAD is to 
collect real-time data on sensor status and activations, which indicate potential terrorist, smuggler or illegal alien movement, compile and relay necessary information to other IT systems and USBP personnel, and monitor and relay agent dispatch status and agent safety information.

The purpose/objective of Border Patrol Enforcement Tracking System (BPETS) is to facilitate the management of workforce staffing levels and schedules, vehicle use in assignments, and to track operational metrics including rescues, deaths, turn-backs and got-aways. BPETS includes the following application modules:  Staffing and Duty Assignments, Daily and Bi-Weekly Scheduling, Time and Attendance, Vehicle Assignments, System Administration, and Reports.

Enforce 3 (e3) system is comprised of modules that provide support to United States Border Patrol (USBP) Agents throughout the various workflow stages starting from apprehension to other enforcement activities. e3 modules include e3Processing (including Intake and Detention), e3 Biometrics, Federated Person Query 2 (FPQ2), e3 Prosecutions, and e3 OASISS. e3 also currently provides some services to various Office of Field Operations ports of entry to assist with their inspections. The objective of e3 is to provide a single system option for agents to enter enforcement incidents, record case and detainee information, and provide reporting measures on DHS-established mission, goals, and priorities. This maintenance project includes software refresh and technical standardization activities necessary to continue providing mission capability for USBP.
Software refresh maintenance activities are targeted at improving application workflow and usability as well as issue/defect resolution. These include e3 Processing Pathway Redesign, e3 Mobile Phase 2, FPQ2 enhancements, Common Framework (Bio), and Processing Legacy O&M Releases.
Technical standardization maintenance activities involve upgrades and patches to system software/operating system/browser as well as security patch implementations, establishment of disaster recovery/failover environments, and application changes due to operating environment directives. These include transition/integration to ICAM, remove IE8 Compatibility Mode (Prosecutions), disaster recovery, and Windows 10 transition.

Enterprise Geospatial Information Services (eGIS) provides CBP personnel with enterprise-level geospatial capabilities that allow for the creation, discovery and access of geospatial content within a role-based administration system. Applications within the eGIS suite include the eGIS Map, Universal Location Point Selector (ULPS), eGIS Portal, and REST/KML services. The objective is to provide situational awareness via geospatial systems using near real-time information in order to secure our borders and support the CBP mission. This Maintenance Project includes software refresh and technical standardization activities necessary to continue providing mission capability for USBP.
Software refresh maintenance activities are targeted at improving application workflow and usability as well as issue/defect resolution. These include upgrades to eGIS Map & eGIS Portal Server, ArcGIS Earth Deployment, Admin Tool JavaScript Migration, redesign of Analysis Tools, and System Integration efforts with other USBP applications.
Technical standardization maintenance activities involve upgrades and patches to system software/operating system/browser as well as security patch implementations, establishment of disaster recovery/failover environments, and application changes due to operating environment directives. These include ICAM integration, Windows 10/EDGE, TFS migration to GIT, and operational monitoring.

Intelligent Computer Assisted Detection (ICAD) system is the USBP command and control system supporting real-time border surveillance and monitoring of agent activity/officer safety. The system identifies and classifies intrusion events from surveillance resources including fielded sensors. The objective is to collect real-time data on potential terrorist, smuggler, or illegal alien movement via sensor status and activations, compile and relay necessary information to other IT systems and USBP personnel, and monitor and relay agent dispatch status and safety information. This Maintenance Project includes software refresh and technical standardization activities necessary to continue providing mission capability to the field. 
Software refresh maintenance activities are targeted at improving application workflow and usability as well as issue/defect resolution. These include replacement of ICAD III, surveillance processors, and I4Live; ICAD Sensor Management updates, instituting legacy software bug fixes; and implementing TSM/AVP/BFT improvements.
Technical standardization maintenance activities involve upgrades and patches to system software/operating system/browser as well as security patch implementations, hardware technology fixes/refresh, establishment of disaster recovery/failover environments, and application changes due to operating environment directives. These include replacement of fielded equipment, implementing security patches and other hardware fresh activities that ensure reliable hardware for mission critical systems.

Border Patrol Enforcement Tracking System (BPETS) facilitates the management of workforce staffing levels and schedules, vehicle use in assignments, and tracking of operational metrics including rescues, deaths, turn-backs and got-aways. BPETS includes the following application modules: Staffing and Duty Assignments, Daily and Bi-Weekly Scheduling, Time and Attendance, Vehicle Assignments, System Administration, and Reports. This Maintenance Project includes the software refresh and technical standardization activities needed to provide BPETS mission capability.
Software refresh maintenance activities are targeted at improving application workflow and usability as well as issue/defect resolution. These include updates to OPM-71 Master Leave, DHS time/attendance solution integration, and Op Orders transition.

Enforce 3 (e3) system is comprised of modules that provide support to United States Border Patrol (USBP) Agents throughout the various workflow stages starting from apprehension to other enforcement activities. e3 modules include e3Processing (including Intake and Detention), e3 Biometrics, Federated Person Query 2 (FPQ2), e3 Prosecutions, and e3 OASISS. e3 also currently provides some services to various Office of Field Operations ports of entry to assist with their inspections. The objective of e3 is to provide a single system option for agents to enter enforcement incidents, record case and detainee information, and provide reporting measures on DHS-established mission, goals, and priorities. This maintenance project includes software refresh and technical standardization activities necessary to continue providing mission capability for USBP.
e3 software refresh in FY19 will consist of application software usability and workflow improvements, as well as issue and defect resolution.
e3 technical standardization in FY19 will consist of system software, operating system and browser patches and upgrades; hardware technology fixes and refresh, disaster recovery and fail over environment establishments, security patch implementations and application changes resulting from operating environment directives (e.g., identity management, application monitoring, cloud, and server software).

Enterprise Geospatial Information Services (eGIS) provides CBP personnel with enterprise-level geospatial capabilities that allow for the creation, discovery and access of geospatial content within a role-based administration system. Applications within the eGIS suite include the eGIS Map, Universal Location Point Selector (ULPS), eGIS Portal, and REST/KML services. The objective is to provide situational awareness via geospatial systems using near real-time information in order to secure our borders and support the CBP mission. This Maintenance Project includes software refresh and technical standardization activities necessary to continue providing mission capability for USBP.
eGIS software refresh in FY19 will consist of application software usability and workflow improvements, as well as issue and defect resolution.
eGIS technical standardization in FY19 will consist of system software, operating system and browser patches and upgrades; hardware technology fixes and refresh, disaster recovery and fail over environment establishments, security patch implementations and application changes resulting from operating environment directives (e.g., identity management, application monitoring, cloud, and server software).

Intelligent Computer Assisted Detection (ICAD) system is the USBP command and control system supporting real-time border surveillance and monitoring of agent activity/officer safety. The system identifies and classifies intrusion events from surveillance resources including fielded sensors. The objective is to collect real-time data on potential terrorist, smuggler, or illegal alien movement via sensor status and activations, compile and relay necessary information to other IT systems and USBP personnel, and monitor and relay agent dispatch status and safety information. This Maintenance Project includes software refresh and technical standardization activities necessary to continue providing mission capability to the field. 
ICAD software refresh in FY19 will consist of application software usability and workflow improvements, as well as issue and defect resolution.
ICAD technical standardization in FY19 will consist of system software, operating system and browser patches and upgrades; hardware technology fixes and refresh, disaster recovery and fail over environment establishments, security patch implementations and application changes resulting from operating environment directives (e.g., identity management, application monitoring, cloud, and server software).

PIR is a centralized Payment Information Repository that contains payment related data from Federal Program Agencies.  PIR is the system of record for Payment Vouchers and allows agencies to reconcile their vouchers before reporting to GWA.  PIR is the only vehicle for NTDOs to report TAS/BETCs via the Standard Reporting Format for reporting in GWA. In addition, PIR provides Business Intelligence and Analytics to federal program agencies based on their ALC authorization.

DSSV is a centralized repository of Agency “wet” signatures for Agency personnel authorized to perform a function during the payment process.  The system supports fundamental internal controls for the payment processes.  DSSV 2.0 will be the technical refresh of the application with deployment to a hosted, shared infrastructure.

NTAP is a cloud based application that integrates the ability readily available in the private sector to receive payments via Commercially available Payment Networks to provide additional options to make electronic payments more available to benefit recipients; these options will assist Payment Management in sustaining the 98% EFT rate for payments while facilitating Treasury's need to address non traditional mechanisms for payment delivery.

Web Based Training is being developed for Certifying Officers that will be an enhanced automated replacement to outdated paper-based pamphlets/booklets; the effectiveness of the training will be demonstrated by the COs’ understanding of their roles and responsibilities which tremendously lower the risk of multi million dollars in payments being erroneous certified.

SPS provides FPAs with a secure, reliable, and convenient method to certify payments. SPS utilizes PKI to maintain confidentiality and integrity of the payments. This systems priority is to lead efforts to develop a Governmentwide solution for IGT buy/sell transfers that will improve the quality and reliability of IGT buy/sell data.  This solution also provides support for Department of Defense’s (DoD) requirements to resolve ongoing audit issues.  Both IPAC and G-Invoicing include functionality that supports these efforts.  The IPAC application's primary purpose is to facilitate the settlement of funds across Federal Program Agencies (FPAs), which includes payment and collection transfers for goods and services (i.e., Buy/sell transactions), fiduciary transfers (i.e., Federal employee benefits), investment and borrowing transactions, and check aftermath activity.  G-Invoicing allows FPAs to define trading partnerships through the General Terms & Conditions (GT&Cs), establish transaction details through orders, and identify/approve transaction settlement information with invoices.  The application is designed to support IGT buy/sell activities in accordance with the Treasury Financial Manual.

This opportunity will allows us to build confidence in the application to start designing our accounting model for future releases.

This project defines the development planning for FY 18.  This fiscal year will represent the Release of PPS 3.1 and the core development stages of Release 4.0.  Release 3.1 development efforts will yield results in several improvement recommendations related to (1) program/project management, and (2) code development/testing approaches. This BCR is a significant step towards ensuring that the functionality that was intended to be delivered in Release 3.0 is delivered in its entirety through subsequent patch releases and Release 3.1.  Release 4.0 is the beginning phase of building the functionality needed to support the decommission of TCIS (Treasury Check Information System) and TRACS (Treasury Receivable Accounting and Collections System).  Release 4.0 has been divided into 3 Phases: Check Reconciliation, Check Claims, and Portal Design.  This new capability will enable Federal Agencies to see the lifecycle of their check claims that deal with status of checks issued, file processing, various flavors of check cancellations and exceptions, and accounting reporting at detailed and summary level. The FY 18 development efforts will concentrate on Phase 1 Check Reconciliation and will also set the stage for Phase 2 & 3 to be completed in FY 19.  Phase 1 (Check Reconciliation) has been divided into four parts and is reflected in the FY 18 schedule.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
The Hospital Quality Reporting System is a quality reporting program where participating hospitals provide CMS with data to help consumers make more informed decisions about their health care. The data is available at www.hospitalcompare.hhs.gov and www.data.medicare.gov. Through legislation, CMS is authorized to pay hospitals a higher annual update to their payment rates if they successfully report designated quality measures. The program began with the Inpatient Quality Reporting Program and now represents several health care provider types (no longer just “hospitals”).
 
The Hospital IQR Program was developed as a result of the Medicare Prescription Drug, Improvement and Modernization Act (MMA) of 2003. Section 5001(a) of Pub. 109-171 of the Deficit Reduction Act (DRA) of 2005 provided new requirements for the Hospital IQR Program, which built on the voluntary Hospital Quality Initiative.
 
The Hospital IQR Program requires "sub-section (d)" hospitals to submit data for specific quality measures for health conditions common among people with Medicare, and which typically result in hospitalization. If they successfully participate in the program, they are eligible to receive their full Medicare reimbursement (of which CMS withholds a percentage until they successfully meet the annual criteria).

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: CMS has implemented quality measure reporting programs for multiple settings of care.These programs are intended to promote higher quality and more efficient health care of Medicare beneficiaries. The reporting of quality measures for ambulatory services is intended to encourage clinicians to improve their quality of care and to empower consumers with information to make more educated health care decisions.CMS is seeking to align payment for high quality of care across settings through the Physician Quality Reporting System (PQRS, the Medicare EHR Incentive Program (MU) and the Physician Value-Based Modifier (VBM) program. These payment adjustments are meant to synthesize CMS’ efforts to improve the quality and value of health care delivered in the United States and to shift the Medicare fee for service program away from paying providers based solely on the volume of services and instead paying them for quality and value of care. CMS provides tools to providers that enable them to measure and monitor resource use and costs. Through the combination of quality metrics, resource utilization tools and cost information, the framework for the development of measures of efficiency have been established. Providers are rewarded for the delivery of high quality, low cost care and encouraged to compete on the basis of quality and cost.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: CMS Quality Improvement Organizations (QIO) Information Systems
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
The Peer Review Improvement Act of 1982 (Title I, subtitle C of the Tax Equity and Fiscal Responsibility Act of 1982 (TEFRA), Pub. L. 97–248) amended Part B of title XI of the Social Security Act (the Act) by establishing the Utilization and Quality Control Peer Review Organization program, now known as the Quality Improvement Organizations (QIOs). The Health and Human Services department of the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services administers the QIO contracts.
QIOs work under contract on strategic initiatives and projects that seek to achieve CMS’s aims of better health care, better health and lower healthcare costs through improvement for all Medicare beneficiaries. CMS anticipates their efforts will likely have a secondary effect of aiding in the transformation of the health care system. The QIO goals align with CMS’s achievement of the National Quality Strategy (NQS) and the CMS Quality Strategy along with the other goals, recommendations, and priorities. QIOs review medical care, help beneficiaries with complaints about the quality of care, and implement improvements across the spectrum of care. Beginning with the 11th SoW in August 1, 2014, QIO contracts are 5 years in length and has two types of QIO contractors. Beneficiary and Family Centered Care QIOs and Quality Innovation Network QIOs. BFCC-QIOs perform medical review and QIN-QIOs develop and work with providers on quality improvement activities.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Investment Title: FDA CTP Regulatory Compliance and Inspection
Project Name: FDA CTP RCI Case Management System (CCMS)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The objective of this project is to develop and implement an IT system which can be used to manage Tobacco Civil Money Penalty (CMP) and No-Tobacco-Sale Order (NTSO) cases that are brought before an ALJ.  The CCMS Application will be utilizing the Microsoft Dynamics CRM 2013 software.  OCE will be spearheading the development of the system on behalf of the CCMS.  FDA CCMS Application will function as a repository for all documents associated with cases brought by CTP against violating tobacco retailers.   The IT system will also function as a case tracking system for case management to be used by the ALJ to ensure statutorily mandated deadlines are met.  To support its compliance and enforcement activities, CCMS will allow close collaboration with ALJ.  On average, there are 10 or fewer documents for cases that quickly close without a hearing, and those cases are a majority of the cases reviewed by the ALJ.  Cases that require a hearing may have 50 or more documents associated with them.  In FY14, there were over 1000 CMP cases brought by CTP before the ALJ, and this number is expected to grow over time.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: Project is in development. There is no routine production rollout during this phase.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The End Stage Renal Disease Quality Reporting System (EQRS) is a consolidation of IT systems - CROWNWeb, REMIS, and ESRD QIP - that supports the Medicare End Stage Renal Disease (ESRD) Program. The ESRD Program is a national health insurance program for people with irreversible kidney failure. Established in 1972, this program led to the creation and maintenance by CMS of a comprehensive patient registry for the entire ESRD population in the United States. Maintaining this patient registry requires the submission of patient/clinical/provider data as well as the production of performance analyses on quality data for the CMS ESRD program. Each of the three systems - - CROWNWeb, REMIS, and ESRD QIP – support the registry, the ESRD program, and EQRS consolidation.

In 2015, FEMA managed 40-plus active grant programs across nine separate Information Technology (IT) systems, to support the Department of Homeland Security (DHS) missions in response, recovery, mitigation, and preparedness. Through the GMM, FEMA is working to integrate the 40-plus programs by establishing a single grants management IT platform for their operations, and, where possible, a common grants management life cycle and unified processes. The objectives of the GMM initiative are to:
•           Simplify the grants life cycle process.
•           Improve the timeliness of funding to support survivors and facilitate community resiliency.
•           Improve the allocation of grant funds across the emergency management community.
•           Streamline and improve business performance by improving business processes and supporting decision-making.
•           Improve business intelligence and decision-making by increasing access to data.
•           Improve compliance with regulations and statutes.
•           Reduce overall sustainment costs by consolidating legacy systems into a single grants management IT platform.
Core foundational architecture necessary to operate HART.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: Using waterfall methodology for Increment 1.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
The Mobile Collections & Receipt (MCR) pilot is intended to modernize collections in the field by allowing payments to be collected at locations that do not have cash registers (e.g., cruise ship ports, ferry ports, private vessel marinas, commercial vessel docks, small airports, low volume land crossings) and otherwise must collect manual payments (i.e., cash, checks) and issue a manual receipt using the U.S Customs and Border Protection (CBP) Form 368 and a Tonnage Tax Form 1002.
The MCR pilot will provide a payment collection solution that can be used on a mobile device, a tablet, or a standard desktop computer, accept electronic payment methods, and, through a direct interface to CBP’s back end systems, remove the need for manual data entry after the payment is collected. Furthermore, the MCR pilot will incorporate features that decrease the time it takes for CBP Officers (CBPOs) in the field require to collect a payment and issue a receipt, in order to lay the foundation for an Alternative Analysis evaluating the approach for the migration, consolidation, reporting and analysis of all CBP revenue collections.
The major objectives for/of the MCR Pilot are listed as follows: 
- Streamline collection process by reducing time spent preparing a manual 368 receipt and Form 1002, allowing officers to focus on mission essential functions.
-  Eliminate all manual supporting processes associated with the paper 368 and 1002, including manual transcription of data into CBP systems, maintaining paper documentation, maintaining security, conducting audits, and issuance of 368 books.
- Codify, publish, and maintain business rules for collections outside the cash register environment among all ports (e.g., fee changes, separation of collections that cannot be on the same receipt).
- Remove void processes associated with handwriting mistakes in the amount section of the 368 form.
- Capture all data on 368 and 1002 electronically and perform data analytics.
SDLC Methodology: 3 - Not Primarily a Software Development Project

Project Name: Transition of GOES and DTOPS collections to SAP
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
For this technology demonstrator project, Rev Mod will develop a proof of concept where the migration of GOES/DTOPS collections to SAP is evaluated and tested in order to lay the foundation for an Alternative Analysis evaluating the approach for the migration, consolidation, reporting and analysis of all CBP revenue collections.
The Global Entry Online Enrollment System (GOES) is an Internet web application which enables the public to apply for Trusted Traveler Programs.  GOES facilitates the payment of a non-refundable application fee by credit card or ACH debit. Between the different programs GOES processes several thousand payments on an average day.
The Decal/Transponder Online Payment System (DTOPS) allows users to purchase, renew, transfer, and exchange user fee decals and transponders for their conveyance.
While serving quite different purposes/programs GOES and DTOPS are very similar from a “collections perspective”: The web application (GOES/DTOPS) sends activities to Pay.gov, and, once successfully processed, to CBP’s revenue system, ACS. Payments are being settled by Pay.gov and its banking partners (such as VANTIV for credit card payments), which in turn deposit the funds into CBP’s account at the Federal Reserve Bank. ACS receives the collections information from Pay.gov and clears receivables established based on the applications GOES and DTOPS send to ACS. In case of failed payments (e.g., credit card chargebacks) ACS will send notification to GOES/DTOPS and the corresponding application will be denied. In this case the Revenue group in Indianapolis will bill the traveler.
Rev Mod will leverage existing SAP capabilities in this technology demonstrator.
SDLC Methodology: 3 - Not Primarily a Software Development Project

Project Name: Migration of Indy LAN capabilities to SAP
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
For this technology demonstrator project, Rev Mod will develop a proof of concept where the migration of these specific collections to SAP is evaluated and tested in order to lay the foundation for an Alternative Analysis evaluating the approach for the migration, consolidation, reporting and analysis of all CBP revenue collections.  In December of 2015 Office of Finance (OF) Financial Systems Division (FSD) (Revenue, NFC, AAMD, FME, OIT and ACE) reviewed 19 Indianapolis Local Area Network (Indy LAN) systems which are mostly part of CBP’s Bill-to-Collect process area.  These systems are databases which are housed within the Indianapolis LAN. The Indy LAN systems need to be removed and / or replaced onto approved CBP systems, in order to mitigate ongoing security and standardization concerns.
Of the 19 systems, a high-level proof of concept was evaluated for four (4) of the systems to test a migration to SAP during this pilot project. 
The four systems included in this proof of concept are:
1. Bankruptcy: 
The Bankruptcy LAN Database tracks dates and pertinent data for complying with the Bankruptcy Court claims filing deadlines. Each stage of the bankruptcy case is tracked and the database allows CBP to monitor its recovery rates based on claims filed.  
2. Promissory Notes
The Promissory Notes LAN Database was developed to record and track all executed Promissory Notes entered into where the principal totals more than $2,000. The database calculates the repayment schedule/amortization schedule for the promissory note using the appropriate interest rates and tracks the timeliness of the promissory note payments.
3. Harbor Maintenance Fees (HMF)
The Harbor Maintenance Fees (HMF) LAN Database records and tracks all HMF payments submitted to the Revenue Division and prepares deposit and collection detail information to be uploaded to ACS. Check payments are added manually to the Check Tracker LAN Database and payments received through U.S. Treas.

Investment Title: Centralized Data Collection and Integration System (CDCIS)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
The objective of this project is to develop a business process management solution to support more than 600 forms and retire the legacy eForms solution in the myData system. The budget includes the costs for the development, testing, deployment, operations and maintenance, change management and communications for the myData system. It also covers the ServiceNow licenses for the department, specifically 10,000 Service Management Suite with Platform Runtime licenses for internal use, as well as 110,000 legacy request module licenses.

Expected outcomes include a cloud-based, more robust solution that centralizes and standardizes the data collection needs of approximately 171 offices expending fewer man hours using ServiceNow as a platform. This solution addressed an increasing number of security violations over the last few years in the legacy eForms system. myData enables the department to improve its compliance with the Paperwork Reduction Act (PRA) by reducing the need for Department personnel to pursue inefficient stop/gap measures to satisfy evolving needs not met by the existing eForms solution and mitigated the security risks with a more secure system. By developing a common platform that leverages an enterprise licensing model, the Department reduces the cost of disparate licenses and eliminate redundant development efforts. Centralization also reduces duplicate data entry by bureaus within the Department and increases visibility to enable greater data-driven insights. Another benefit is enhanced unified system security through management of a single certified system that meets guidelines and regulations for sensitive and personal information collected on the unclassified system.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The CWF has four scheduled (January, April, July and October) quarterly releases that control, implement, and update the software due to legislative mandates that dictate the amount of payment for services or coverage levels.  The CWF also implements changes needed to support the Medicare Administrative Contractors (MACs) authority for the Medicare FFS Program.  Software changes for the claims processing operations are managed in quarterly releases developed through a change control process that begins with the Medicare Change Control Board (MCCB) review and prioritization of pending requests.  The FFS Operations Board approves the quarterly releases with oversight by the FFS Governance Council and manages/integrates day-to-day operations of the FFS program across CMS.  Error-free releases that implement legislative mandates with minimal interruption to processing ensure that beneficiaries receive the correct service and providers receive the correct payment.

Agency Name: Department of Health and Human Services
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
The Affordable Care Act (ACA), signed into law on March 23, 2010, provided the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS) with critical tools to implement important strategic changes in pursuing fraud, waste, and abuse. In this context, the Center for Program Integrity (CPI) was formed in April 2010 by combining separate program integrity (PI) groups for Medicare and Medicaid. CPI serves as the focal point for the prevention and detection of all national and State-wide fraud and abuse issues in the Medicare and Medicaid programs. 
In 2013, CPI announced a strategy to implement a unified PI contract, the Unified Program Integrity Contractor (UPIC). To provide this unified approach, CMS requires a Unified Case Management (UCM) system that aligns with the business goals of supporting the workload of PI contractors in different jurisdictions across the Medicare and Medicaid programs. Through the UCM system, CMS will be laying the foundation for a nationally coordinated campaign against fraud, waste, and abuse that is enabled by timely sharing of actionable data and information.

Project Name: Trust Funds (TF) System Replacement Development and implementation
Objectives / Expected Outcomes:
(1) Ensure fiscal integrity by maintaining accountability and control of financial and business processes.
(2) Improve program performance, mission support, and decision-making at all levels of the agency by providing management information that links financial, business, and program performance.
(3) Improve transparency and accountability through increased standardization and the elimination of redundant systems and processes.
(4) Provide an integrated information architecture process and structure that directly supports OPM’s mission and business information management requirements.
(5) Provide timely, accurate and consistent information on the financial condition of the organization and its programs. 
(6) Provide a solution that economically and efficiently leverages technology over the solution’s life cycle and accommodates changes in Federal laws, regulations and financial and business management mandates, directives, and policies.
(7) Clearly define and automate adherence to business rules. The business rules will enable system users to more easily follow required practices derived from federal regulations, OPM policies, and industry best practices.
(80) Use current, proven technology and regularly upgraded software to allow a long system lifespan, gain economies of scale, leverage an existing support network, and ultimately minimize the solution’s Total Cost of Ownership (TCO).

These activities will identify new and innovative technological approaches and data management solutions and services available to address existing gaps related to trust funds accounting, management and technology that are preventing the agency from fulfilling long term strategic goals efficiently and cost effectively.

Project Name: Appeals Modernization - Board of Veterans' Appeals (BVA)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Funding is requested for end-to-end Appeals Modernization throughout the Department, which will leverage people, process and technology enhancements to mitigate the risk inherent in disjointed manual appeals processing from multiple business lines, causing increased wait times for Veterans and their families.  Appeals Modernization will allow the Department to contain and ultimately reduce the VA appeals inventory, which currently stands at over 380,000 appeals, and efficiently process future appeals workload. Appeals Modernization will enable the Department to process appeals decisions more efficiently, which will reduce wait times for Veterans and their families. Additionally, this initiative will ultimately reduce error from manual appeals processing and manual work-arounds currently in place to address technology voids.

Project Name: Appeals Modernization - Board of Veterans’ Appeals (BVA) Phase 2
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Appeals Modernization effort will continue to improve and streamline the end-to-end appeals process by increasing efficiency and providing transparency to all stakeholders involved in the multi-step process. This Board of Veterans’ Appeals initiative will continue to result in the creation of a new tool, Caseflow, that will replace Veterans Appeals Control and Location System (VACOLS) with tools and functionality that are required to more effectively and securely process appeals. Appeals Modernization will improve appeals processing throughout the Department in order to better serve Veterans and their families. This project incorporates significant changes to the legacy appeals system brought on by the enactment of the Veterans Appeals Improvement and Modernization Act of 2017 (AMA), which was signed into law on August 23, 2017, during the midst of this ongoing project. AMA significantly increased the complexity of the appeals process, and required the Appeals Modernization project to change direction and focus.

Project Name: Pharmacy Re-Engineering - PRE Pharmacy Product System National (PPS-N)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Pharmacy Product System National (PPS - N) Pharmacy Re-Engineering (PRE) projectsfocus on critical patient safety issues with the legacy pharmacy system by providing clinical decision support (CDS) tools to crosscheck drugs and doses in medication orders at the point of order entry to reduce the frequency of adverse drug events and save lives.PPS-N will replace the legacy National Drug File (NDF) Management System. The legacy NDF system is expensive to maintain and the manual process of both finding and adding new drug information takes greater than 60 days. The new PPS-N uses automation to find, capture and store new drugs information into a national repository, thereby making drug information such as names, drug codes and ingredients instantly available in the order checks. PPS-N will also allow individual sites to locally define drug variants totrigger order checks per policy for improved patient safety. This project works together with PRE's PECS-MOCHA project to provide accurate up-to-date order checks thereby reducing time for order and prescription processing, reducing adverse drug events and saving lives. PRE serves VAs mission for better business & customer results by reducing healthcare costs and employee workload while improving care for Veterans.

The Referrals and Authorizations  (R&A) solution will be the tool used by all Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) CC staff located throughout 142 VA medical centers to review referrals and generate authorizations for all Veterans receiving care through the Veterans Choice Program. The R&A solution will be an integrated component of the VA Community Care Information Technology (IT) architecture that allows Veterans to receive care from non-VA Community Providers.

The VHA Office of Community Care (OCC), Revenue Operations (RO), Consolidated Patient Account Centers (CPAC) needs to modify the existing COTS Huron work flow tool to comply with mandated legislation requiring VHA to collect copay funds from Veterans and insurance funds from insurance companies with which Veterans have polices.  Updates to the CPAC workflow tool are needed because, effective 2/13/2017, Choice Contractor claims data no longer flows through the VA clearinghouse into VHA systems and into the CPAC workflow tool. Choice Contractor billing data is transmitted directly from the Choice Contractors (aka TPAs -- TriWest & HealthShare) to the Financial Services Center (FSC) and into the FSC claims processing system where payments are prepared. A file containing invoice and payment information must be prepared and sent to the CPAC workflow tool via the PIT system.

Project Name: Business Information Office Business Intelligence Solution (BIO BIS)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: When Veterans receive care from VA for non-service-connected conditions, VA is allowed to bill the Veterans' private health insurers and retain these third-party collections to supplement its appropriations for health care.  In addition, VA may also bill and collect co-pays from a number of Veterans who receive non-service-connected care or prescriptions from VA medical facilities.  VHA  established Chief Business Office (CBO) in 2002 to the processes to bill and collect, provide corporate oversight, and further professionalize healthcare revenue activities.  Since 2003, CBO's  POWER reporting system (POWER/POWER PLUS) has supported VHA's efforts to improve performance in its revenue collections business operations by providing accurate, reliable, and up-to-date outcome and performance measure information.  The performance information in POWER/POWER Plus has allowed VHA management to create reports to manage, analyze, and monitor metrics for revenue tracking, yielding over $3 billion per year.  The performance of this system and its reporting capabilities are critical to maximizing revenue collections.  Inconsistency or variation of data will negatively impact revenue collections, which would result in a reduction of funding provided to VA medical centers and ultimately negatively impact the Veterans with regard to obtaining healthcare service.  Therefor it is critical to maintain technical expertise and continuity of services to reduce variation in reporting and minimize the risk for inconsistent and/or inaccurate data analyzed by high echelon Government personnel and utilized in budgetary planning and decision-making as well as revenue collection.Over the years, dependency on the POWER/POWER Plus reports has grown.  In order to keep up with the demand of emerging requirements and management's need for transparency, CBO needs to expand and enhance the current system.  POWER/POWER Plus is resting on a legacy platform and outdated software.  We have outgrown the current host-site, support, and environment.  In order to provide accurate and reliable information, IT Funding is needed to move BIO Business Intelligence Solution (BIO BIS), (new and enhanced reporting system) to Austin (AITC) or another VA internal/external host-site for continued database and resource support.  There are no sub-programs associated with this.

Project Name: Sustainment of VistA Standardization and Virtualization
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The goals of the VSV project are:•	Develop a plan for VistA code standardization•	Develop a plan for VistA Data Dictionary standardization•	Identify non-standard code and data dictionary entries for each site•	Identify FileMan by-passes such as improper direct “Sets” and “Kills”•	Develop a plan and method to clean up incorrect terms and misspelled terms, preserving the current record and pointers•	Develop a plan to standardize configuration files•	Develop a plan to create libraries for Class III code, device code and compiled routines•	Identify files and routines no longer in use to remove from VistA•	Create a single Titanium image of VistA that is the de facto “Standard VistA”•	Remediate and adjudicate waivers from local facilities•	Establish and enforce governance process to prevent unauthorized changes to the code base •	Develop method to have a VistA with the smallest footprint possible, focused only on the EHR •	Develop a plan to move VistA to the Commercial Cloud•	Develop a method to make a virtual Single Logical VistA Instance (vSLVI)•	Develop an architecture and plan for continued operations if a site is disconnected from the vSLVI•	Develop a decommissioning and divestiture plan for Legacy VistA systems.
Release Every Six Mo Comment: Project will be in various phases of test for the first 6 to 12 months.

Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Telehealth Management Platform (TMP) program will develop an application that is built upon the Microsoft Consumer Off-the-Shelf (COTS) Customer Relations Management (CRM) solution, which has been optimized specifically for VHA’s Office of Connected Care Telehealth.  TMP will provide VHA Clinical Schedulers and Providers with a single interface to manage Telehealth appointments, provider credential  validation, control over VA Video Connect (VVC) clinical video teleconferencing solution by automatically issuing URL links for the Patient and Provider with associated PINS for one-touch video connectivity. The TMP will have bi-directional secure interfaces to the VA VistA /Computerized Patient Record System (CPRS) for synchronous read/write capability so all required resources to coordinate Provider’s calendars, room resources as well as video service/equipment and required ancillary equipment availability and scheduling. Project Name: Radiation Oncology Peer Review Software Hosting
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The OIG Report "Radiation Safety in Veterans Health Administration Facilities" focused on areas of greatest potential harm to patients.  This focus included radiation therapy.  Benefits from more accurate diagnosis are generally considered to exceed risks inherent in radiation exposure.  Compliance with key elements of ACR recommendations with required physician peer review is a key element in ensuring patient safety and quality care.  This peer review project will give centers the ability to do physician peer review online using the VA server.  The IT solution will consist of an intranet based server with the peer review software that will be accessible to all our VA Radiation Oncology clinics to facilitate peer review. Commercially available and FDA approved peer review software packages have no dependencies or other external systems or policies. It will only require VA intranet storage and application server hardware.

Yes, this is a key component to addressing HR4486 “The House passed the VA 15 budget bill, which on page 34 states:  Provided further, That funds under this heading may be used by the Interagency Program Office through the Department of Veterans Affairs to develop a standard data reference terminology model Section 713 of the National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2014 (titled “Electronic health records of the Department of Defense and the Department of Veterans Affairs”) states the following: “No later than October 1, 2014, all health care data contained in the Department of Defense AHLTA and the Department of Veterans Affairs VistA systems shall be computable in real time and comply with the existing national data standards and have a process in place to ensure data is standardized as national standards continue to evolve.”  http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CPRT-113HPRT86280/pdf/CPRT-113HPRT86280.pdf, Page 128, Item (g)(1)..

Project Name: Collaborative Terminology Tooling and Data Management
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Knowledge Based Systems (KBS) and Standards and Terminology Services (STS) propose VA establish a collaborative Enterprise Terminology Service (ETS) that bridges clinical and technical domains in order to address both the Congressional and Executive mandates for interoperability, standardization, computability and meaningful use.  The ETS is foundational to establishment and maintenance of robust interoperability with VA partners, such as the Department of Defense (DoD) and Veterans Benefits Administration (VBA) and will address longstanding Congressional concerns.

OIT Leadership is pursuing a digital platform to leverage a microservices architecture to bring together a number of key VA systems including CRM, EHR, HR, SCM, and create enable OIT to rapidly develop applications on standardized APIs. Existing systems pose business risk, because they were built as custom IT products that are increasingly difficult and expensive to maintain and enhance, and can only leverage manual data inputs rather than automated system data, with little to no integration with newer systems.  The high level of manual entry conflicts with business requirements for greater data integrity and frustrates auditors and Congressional oversight. These and other risks involved in operating this environment have made the development of a micorservices based digital platform a top priority for OIT leadership.  This will allow the VA to collect and combine critical information to help VA provide enhanced services to the veteran.

Project Name: Million Veterans Program (MVP) - CHAMPION VA-DOE Doss Center Phase 2
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: In support of the joint Department of Energy (DOE) and Veterans Health Administration (VHA) Million Veteran Program (MVP) CHAMPION initiative to advance cancer research and find cures for Veterans and the world at large, this effort funds a new part B tasking under an existing Interagency Agreement (IAA) with the DOE.  It will expand on work completed to date to develop/implement genomic analytical tools and multi-directional processing in support of VHA research projects.  Project is required in support of the Statement of Principle titled MVP CHAMPION between the Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) and the DOE signed June 16, 2016. The VA-DOE Doss Center’s mission is to improve Veterans’ health by enabling and accelerating scientific discoveries that result in better care and outcomes. Combining the world’s richest genomic and longitudinal data (VA) with the world’s best computational infrastructure and advanced analytics (DOE), allows the VA-DOE Doss Center to serve the medical scientific community in their drive to apply new science to improving Veterans’ health.

Project Name: Austin Financial Service Center Voice System Replacement Project
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Project Summary:  The Financial Services Center (FSC) Chief of Staff is requesting a new Voice System (VS) Project for the FSC, which will replace the current legacy voice systems and accommodate: a surge in staffing, larger than normal grow of their voice systems capacity, and a more seamless interface to required ancillary systems; such as Customer Relationship Management (CRM), Customer Process Manager (CPM) and virtual call center agents     Project Justification: The current VS (NEC SV 8500) is nearly nine (9) years old. The current VS cannot provide a seamless integration into the PegaSystems Business Platform’s Customer Relationship Management (CRM) and Customer Process Manager (CPM). The PegaSystems Business Platform consolidates different repositories of financial and Veteran information into a single repository that the FSC Contact Center relies upon when communicating with Veterans, private sector Medical Billing vendors, insurance carriers, and enterprise internal VA support systems such as Concur and VA Time and Attendance System (VATAS). This issue is the major decision point for a replacement.

Program Management, Governance, Implementation Capability, and Organization Change Support:  Assist OIT in standing up a Cloud Computing Management Office (CCMO) that provides the program management capabilities needed to assess, plan, manage, and operate a VA enterprise cloud computing environment;  Help establish VA cloud governance; Support and advise VA project teams in cloud project planning; Assist VA in preparing for and managing change associated with the implementation of the cloud program; Assist VA in developing and maintaining a cloud computing strategic direction ; VAEC Architecture, Requirements, Design, and Operations Planning: Assist in the review, analysis, and make recommendations to optimize the VAEC architecture; Advise VA in the planning for VAEC operations and maintenance; Enterprise Cloud Application Migration: Assist VA in establishing a standardized, repeatable migration technical approach; Assess selected systems for cloud suitability and recommend migration type ; Infrastructure Engineering Planning:  Assist VA in IT infrastructure modernization through data center consolidation, modernization and enhancement end-user .services and data storage, and unified communications : VAEC Operations: Assist in the maintenance and updating of the “as-is” VAEC architecture; Assist VA in the day-to-day systems management and operations of VAEC, including performance and usage reporting, event management, configuration management, and security in the VAEC virtual infrastructure; VAEC Application Migration: Execution support for migrating new and legacy VA applications and services to cloud computing (VAEC and approved external clouds); Infrastructure Engineering Support; Execution support for continuous improvement of VA’s IT infrastructure through the modernization of end-user services and data storage.

Deliver minor enhancements to two separate case management systems, the iCERT case management system and the PERM case management system, provide quarterly EIN and OES updates, and provide application development and support.   iCERT and PERM aim to allow OFLC to accomplish its mission of processing employer-based labor certification and prevailing wage applications electronically.
